80195079937/page/125 125\u2013133] |title=The World's Writing Systems |editor-first1=Peter T. |editor-last1=Daniels |editor-first2=William |editor-last2=Bright |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-19-507993-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195079937/page/125 }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1400 BC || [[Luwian language|Luwian]] || [[Hieroglyphic Luwian]] monumental inscriptions, Cuneiform Luwian tablets in the Hattusa archives{{sfnp|Baldi|2002|p=30}} || Isolated hieroglyphs appear on seals from the 18th century BC.{{sfnp|Baldi|2002|p=30}}\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1400 BC || [[Hattic language|Hattic]] || [[Hittite texts]] CTH 725\u2013745 || \n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1300 BC || [[Ugaritic language|Ugaritic]] || Tablets from [[Ugarit]]<ref>{{cite book|first=Dennis|last=Pardee|chapter=Ugaritic|pages=5\u201335|editor-first=Roger D.|editor-last=Woodard|title=The Ancient Languages of Syria-Palestine and Arabia|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-521-68498-9}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1200 BC || [[Old Chinese]] || [[Oracle bone]] and [[Chinese bronze inscriptions|bronze inscriptions]] from the reign of [[Wu Ding]]{{sfnp|Bagley|1999|pp=181\u2013182}}{{sfnp|Keightley|1999|pp=235\u2013237}}<ref>{{cite book|first=John|last=DeFrancis|title=Visible Speech. The Diverse Oneness of Writing Systems|chapter=Chinese|pages=89\u2013121|chapterurl=http://www.pinyin.info/readings/texts/visible/index.html|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|year=1989|isbn=978-0-8248-1207-2}}</ref> || \n|}\n<gallery heights=\"150px\" widths=\"150px\">\nFile:Peribsen2.JPG|Seal impression from the tomb of [[Seth-Peribsen]], containing the oldest known complete sentence in [[Egyptian language|Egyptian]], {{circa|lk=no}} 2690 BC<ref name=\"James Egyptian\"/>\nFile:Letter Luenna Louvre AO4238.jpg|Letter in [[Sumerian cuneiform]] sent by the high-priest Lu'enna, informing the king of [[Lagash]] of his son's death in battle, {{circa|lk=no}} 2400 BC<ref>{{cite web |title=Lettre du grand-pr\u00eatre Lu'enna |publisher=Louvre |url=http://cartelfr.louvre.fr/cartelfr/visite?srv=car_not&idNotice=9732 |access-date=16 September 2018 }}</ref>\nFile:NAMA Linear B tablet of Pylos.jpg|Greek [[Linear B]] tablet from [[Pylos]], recording the distribution of hides, {{circa|lk=no}} 1200 BC\nFile:Shang dynasty inscribed scapula.jpg|Ox scapula inscribed with three records of divinations in the reign of [[Wu Ding]] of the Chinese [[Shang dynasty]], {{circa|lk=no}} 1200 BC\n</gallery>\n\n==First millennium BC==\n\n[[File:Sarcophag of Ahiram inscription.png|thumb|right|upright=2.2|The [[Ahiram]] epitaph is the earliest substantial inscription in [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]].]]\nThe earliest known alphabetic inscriptions, at [[Serabit el-Khadim]] ({{circa|lk=no}} 1500 BC), appear to record a [[Northwest Semitic]] language, though only one or two words have been deciphered.\nIn the [[Early Iron Age]], alphabetic writing spread across the Near East and southern Europe. With the emergence of the [[Brahmic family of scripts]], [[languages of India]] are attested from after about 300 BC.\n\nThere is only fragmentary evidence for languages such as [[Iberian language|Iberian]], [[Tartessian language|Tartessian]], [[Galatian language|Galatian]], [[Thracian language|Thracian]] and [[Messapian language|Messapian]].{{sfnp|Woodard|2008|pp=4, 9, 11}}\nThe [[North Picene language]] of the Novilara Stele from {{circa|lk=no}} 600 BC has not been deciphered.{{sfnp|Woodard|2008|p=4}}\nThe earliest examples of the Central American [[Isthmian script]] date from {{circa|lk=no}} 500 BC, but a proposed decipherment remains controversial.<ref>{{cite book | title = Lost Languages: The Enigma of the World's Undeciphered Scripts | first = Andrew | last = Robinson | publisher = Thames & Hudson | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-500-51453-5 | page = 263}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Language !! Attestation !! Notes\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1000 BC || [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]] || [[Ahiram]] epitaph<ref>{{cite journal | first = Edward M. | last = Cook | title = On the Linguistic Dating of the Phoenician Ahiram Inscription (KAI 1) | journal = Journal of Near Eastern Studies | volume = 53 | issue = 1 | year = 1994 | pages = 33\u201336 | jstor = 545356 | doi=10.1086/373654}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 10th century BC || [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] || royal inscriptions from [[Aramean]] city-states<ref>{{cite book|first=Stuart|last=Creason|chapter=Aramaic|pages=108\u2013144|editor-first=Roger D.|editor-last=Woodard|title=The Ancient Languages of Syria-Palestine and Arabia|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-521-68498-9}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 10th century BC || [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] or [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]] || [[Gezer calendar]]<ref>{{cite journal| title = The Gezer Calendar and Northwest Semitic Linguistics | first = Daniel | last = Silvan | journal = Israel Exploration Journal | volume = 48 | issue = 1/2 | year = 1998 | pages = 101\u2013105 | jstor = 27926502}}</ref> || [[Paleo-Hebrew]] employed a slightly modified Phoenician alphabet, hence the uncertainty between which is attested to here. \n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 850 BC || [[Ammonite language|Ammonite]] || [[Amman Citadel Inscription]]<ref>{{cite journal | title = The Ammn Citadel Inscription: A New Collation | first = William J. | last = Fulco | journal = Bulletin of the American Schools of Oriental Research | volume = 230 | issue = 230 | year = 1978 | pages = 39\u201343 | jstor = 1356612 | doi = 10.2307/1356612 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 840 BC || [[Moabite language|Moabite]] || [[Mesha Stele]] ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 800 BC || [[Phrygian language|Phrygian]] || Paleo-Phrygian inscriptions at [[Gordion]]<ref>{{cite book | first = Claude | last = Brixhe | chapter = Phrygian | pages = 69\u201380 | title = The Ancient Languages of Asia Minor | editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodard | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68496-5 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 8th century BC || [[Sabaean language|Sabaean]] ([[Old South Arabian]]) || mainly [[boustrophedon]] inscriptions from Yemen<ref>{{cite book|first1=Norbert|last1=Nebes|first2=Peter|last2=Stein|chapter=Ancient South Arabian|pages=145\u2013178|editor-first=Roger D.|editor-last=Woodard|title=The Ancient Languages of Syria-Palestine and Arabia|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-521-68498-9}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 700 BC || [[Etruscan language|Etruscan]] || proto-Corinthian vase found at [[Tarquinia]]<ref>{{cite book | title = Part 2 of The Cambridge Ancient History: The Hellenistic World | editors = F. W. Walbank, A. E. Astin, M. W. Frederiksen | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 1990 | isbn = 978-0-521-23446-7 | page = 12 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 7th century BC || [[Latin]] || ''Vetusia'' Inscription and ''[[Praeneste fibula|Fibula Praenestina]]''<ref>{{cite book|title=A Companion to the Latin Language|first=James|last=Clackson|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4443-4336-6|page=13|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HgQjpHUIBWkC&pg=PA13&lpg=PA13}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 600 BC || [[Lydian language|Lydian]] || inscriptions from [[Sardis]]{{sfnp|Baldi|2002|p=30}} ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 600 BC || [[Carian language|Carian]] || inscriptions from [[Caria]] and Egypt{{sfnp|Baldi|2002|p=30}} ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 600 BC || [[Faliscan language|Faliscan]] || Ceres inscription found at [[Falerii]]<ref>{{cite book | first = Gabri\u00ebl C. L. M. | last = Bakkum | title = The Latin dialect of the Ager Faliscus: 150 years of scholarship, Volume 1 | publisher = University of Amsterdam Press | year = 2009 | pages = 393\u2013406 | isbn = 978-90-5629-562-2 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| early&nbsp;6th&nbsp;century&nbsp;BC || [[Umbrian language|Umbrian]] || text painted on the handle of a [[krater]] found near [[Tolfa]]<ref>{{cite journal | title = Recent Research on Sabellian Inscriptions | given = Rex E. | surname = Wallace | journal = Indo-European Studies Bulletin | volume = 8 | number = 1 | year = 1998 | pages = 1\u20139 }} p. 4.</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 550 BC || [[Taymanitic]] || Esk 168 and 177<ref>{{cite book|first=M.C.A|last=Macdonald|chapter=Ancient North Arabian|pages=179\u2013224|editor-first=Roger D.|editor-last=Woodard|title=The Ancient Languages of Syria-Palestine and Arabia|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-521-68498-9}} p. 181.</ref> || The Taymanitic script is mentioned in an 8th century BC document from [[Carchemish]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=M.C.A |last=Macdonald |title=Reflections on the linguistic map of pre-Islamic Arabia |journal=Arabian Archaeology and Epigraphy |year=2000 |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=28\u201379 |url=http://krc.orient.ox.ac.uk/resources/ociana/publications/reflections.pdf |doi=10.1111/j.1600-0471.2000.aae110106.x }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 550 BC || [[South Picene language|South Picene]] || [[Warrior of Capestrano]]<ref>{{cite book | title = The Blackwell History of the Latin Language | first1 = James | last1 = Clackson | first2 = Geoffrey | last2 = Horrocks | publisher = Blackwell | year = 2007 | isbn = 978-1-4051-6209-8 | page = 49 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| mid-6th century BC || [[Venetic language|Venetic]] || funerary inscriptions at [[Este, Veneto|Este]]<ref>{{cite book | chapter = Venetic | first = Rex E. | last = Wallace | pages = [https://archive.org/details/ancientlanguages00roge/page/124 124\u2013140] | title = The Ancient Languages of Europe | editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodard | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68495-8 | url = https://archive.org/details/ancientlanguages00roge/page/124 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 500 BC || [[Old Persian]] || [[Behistun inscription]] ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 500 BC || [[Lepontic language|Lepontic]] || inscriptions CO-48 from Pristino ([[Como]]) and VA-6 from [[Vergiate]] ([[Varese]])<ref>[http://www.univie.ac.at/lexlep/wiki/Main_Page ''Lexicon Leponticum''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421114857/http://www.univie.ac.at/lexlep/wiki/Main_Page |date=2014-04-21 }}, by David Stifter, Martin Braun and Michela Vignoli, [[University of Vienna]].</ref><ref>{{cite web | first = David | last = Stifter | title = Celtic in northern Italy: Lepontic and Cisalpine Gaulish | year = 2012 | url = http://rootsofeurope.ku.dk/kalender/arkiv_2012/celtic_spring/Lepontisch_WS_2010.pdf | access-date = 24 October 2016 }}</ref> || Inscriptions from the early 6th century consist of isolated names.\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 300 BC || [[Oscan language|Oscan]] || Iovilae from [[Capua]]<ref>{{cite book | title = A Grammar of Oscan and Umbrian: With a Collection of Inscriptions and a Glossary | given = Carl Darling | surname = Buck | author-link = Carl Darling Buck | location = Boston | publisher = The Athenaeum Press | year = 1904 | pages = 247\u2013248 | url = https://archive.org/details/agrammaroscanan00goog | ref = harv }}</ref> || Coin legends date from the late 5th century BC.{{sfnp|Buck|1904|p=4}}\n|-\n| 3rd century BC || [[Gaulish language|Gaulish]] || Transalpine Gaulish inscriptions in Massiliote Greek script<ref>{{cite book | chapter = Continental Celtic | first = Joseph F. | last = Eska | pages = [https://archive.org/details/ancientlanguages00roge/page/165 165\u2013188] | title = The Ancient Languages of Europe | editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodard | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68495-8 | url = https://archive.org/details/ancientlanguages00roge/page/165 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 3rd century BC || [[Volscian language|Volscian]] || Tabula Veliterna{{sfnp|Baldi|2002|p=140}} ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 260 BC || [[Prakrit]] ([[Middle Indo-Aryan]]) || [[Edicts of Ashoka]]<ref name=WS>{{cite book | last=Rogers | first=Henry | author-link= | title=Writing Systems | publisher=Black Publishing | place= | year=2004 | isbn=978-0-631-23464-7}} p. 204</ref>{{sfnp|Pollock|2003|p=60}} || Pottery inscriptions from [[Anuradhapura]] have been dated {{circa|lk=no}} 400 BC.<ref>{{cite book|title=Between the Empires: Society in India 300 BCE to 400 CE|chapter=Inscribed pots, emerging identities|first=Himanshu Prabha| last=Ray|pages=113\u2013143|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2006|editor-first=Patrick|editor-last=Olivelle|isbn=978-0-19-977507-1}}, pp. 121\u2013122.</ref><ref name=\"Coningham 1996\">{{cite journal|title=Passage to India? Anuradhapura and the Early Use of the Brahmi Script| first1=R.A.E.| last1=Coningham | first2=F.R.|last2=Allchin| first3=C.M.| last3=Batt| first4=D.|last4=Lucy |journal= Cambridge Archaeological Journal|volume=6|number=1|year=1996|pages=73\u201397|doi=10.1017/S0959774300001608}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 200 BC || [[Tamil language|Tamil]] || cave inscriptions and potsherds in Tamil Nadu<ref>{{cite book | first = Kamil Veith | last = Zvelebil | title = Companion Studies to the History of Tamil Literature | pages = 122\u2013123 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qAPtq49DZfoC&pg=PA122 | publisher = BRILL | year = 1992 | isbn = 978-90-04-09365-2 }}</ref>{{sfnp|Krishnamurti|2003|p=22}} || 5th century BC inscriptions on potsherds found in Kodumanal, Porunthal and [[Palani]] have been claimed as [[Tamil-Brahmi]],<ref>{{Cite book\n| chapter=Situating Iron Age moduments in South Asia: a textual and ethnographic approach\n| first=K. |last=Rajan\n| url=https://books.google.com/?id=VAb9CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA311\n| title=A Companion to South Asia in the Past\n| editor1-first=Gwen | editor1-last=Robbins Schug | editor2-first=Subhash R. | editor2-last=Walimbe\n| publisher = Wiley-Blackwell | year=2016| isbn = 978-1-119-05548-8| pages = 310\u2013318\n}} p. 311.</ref><ref>{{Cite book\n| url=http://iks.iitgn.ac.in/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Iron-Age%E2%80%93Early-Historical-transition-in-South-India-K-Rajan.pdf\n| title=Iron Age \u2013 Early Historic Transition in South India: an appraisal\n| first=K. | last=Rajan | publisher = Institute of Archaeology | year=2014| page = 9\n}}</ref> but this is disputed.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Owner's graffiti on pottery from Tissamaharama |first=Harry| last=Falk| journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Arch\u00e4ologie Au\u00dfereurop\u00e4ischer Kulturen |volume=6 | year=2014| page=46, with footnote 2| url=https://www.academia.edu/11754083}} Falk has criticized the Kodumanal and Porunthal claims as \"particularly ill-informed\"; Falk argues that some of the earliest supposed inscriptions are not Brahmi letters at all, but merely misinterpreted non-linguistic [[Megalithic graffiti symbols]], which were used in South India for several centuries during the pre-literate era.</ref> Pottery fragments dated to the 6th century BC and inscribed with personal names have been found at [[Keeladi]],<ref>{{cite report\n| title=Keeladi: an Urban Settlement of Gangam Age on the Banks of the River Vigai\n| editor1-first=R. | editor1-last=Sivanantham | editor2-first=M. | editor2-last=Seran\n| location=Chennai | publisher=Department of Archaeology, Government of Tamil Nadu | year=2019\n| pages=8\u20139, 14\n}}</ref> but the dating is disputed.<ref>{{cite journal\n| title = Experts Question Dates of Script in Tamil Nadu's Keeladi Excavation Report\n| given = Sukanya | surname = Charuchandra\n| journal = The Wire | date = 17 October 2019\n| url = https://thewire.in/the-sciences/keeladi-settlement-tamil-nadu-department-of-archaeology-tamil-brahmi-script-indus-valley-civilisation\n}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{0|{{circa|lk=no}}}} 146 BC || [[Numidian language|East Numidian]] || [[Punic-Libyan Inscription]] at [[Dougga]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Mausoleum of Ateban |url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?place=33644&plaA=33644-3-1 |publisher=British Museum }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 2nd century BC || [[Meroitic language|Meroitic]] || graffiti on the temple of [[Amun]] at Du