z (Aksum) | first = Gene | last = Gragg | pages = 211\u2013237 | title = The Ancient Languages of Mesopotamia, Egypt and Aksum | editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodard | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68497-2 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 350 || [[Cham language|Cham]] || [[\u0110\u00f4ng Y\u00ean Ch\u00e2u inscription]] found near [[Tra Ki\u00eau]]<ref>{{cite book | title = From Ancient Cham to Modern Dialects: Two Thousand Years of Language Contact and Change | first = Graham | last = Thurgood | publisher = University of Hawaii Press | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0-8248-2131-9 | page = 3 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 4th century || [[Gothic language|Gothic]] || [[Gothic Bible]], translated by [[Wulfila]]<ref>{{cite book | chapter = Gothic | first = Jay H. | last = Jasanoff | pages = [https://archive.org/details/ancientlanguages00roge/page/189 189\u2013214] | title = The Ancient Languages of Europe | editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodard | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68495-8 | url = https://archive.org/details/ancientlanguages00roge/page/189 }}</ref> || A few problematic [[Gothic runic inscriptions]] may date to the early 4th century.\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 400 || [[Tocharian languages|Tocharian B]] || THT 274 and similar manuscripts<ref>{{cite book |chapter=A Glimpse into the Tocharian Vinaya Texts |surname=Pan |given=Tao |pages=67\u201392 |chapter-url=https://www.academia.edu/34338196 |title=Rules of Engagement: Medieval Traditions of Buddhist Monastic Regulation |editor1-given=Susan |editor1-surname=Andrews |editor2-given=Jinhua |editor2-surname=Chen |editor3-given=Cuilan |editor3-surname=Liu |publisher=Numata Center for Buddhist Studies |year=2017 |isbn=978-3-89733428-1 }}</ref> || Some Tocharian names and words have been found in Prakrit documents from [[Kror\u00e4n]] dated {{circa|lk=no}} 300.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Bronze Age languages of the Tarim Basin | first