]])\n**4th century AD: [[Germanic languages|Germanic]] ([[Gothic language|Gothic]])\n**9th century AD: [[Balto-Slavic languages|Balto-Slavic]] ([[Old Church Slavonic]])\n*[[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]]: {{circa|lk=no}} 1200 BC\n**{{circa|lk=no}} 1200 BC: [[Old Chinese]]\n**8th century AD: [[Tibeto-Burman]] ([[Tibetic languages|Tibetan]])\n*[[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]]: {{circa|lk=no}} 200 BC ([[Tamil language|Tamil]])\n*[[Mayan languages|Mayan]]: 3rd century AD\n*[[Austronesian languages|Austronesian]]: 4th century AD ([[Cham language|Cham]])\n*[[South Caucasian languages|South Caucasian]]: 5th century ([[Georgian language|Georgian]])\n*[[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian]]: 7th century ([[Udi language|Udi]])\n*[[Austroasiatic]]: 7th century ([[Khmer language|Khmer]])\n*[[Turkic languages|Turkic]]: 8th century ([[Old Turkic]])\n*[[Japonic]]: 8th century\n*[[Nilo-Saharan]]: 8th century ([[Old Nubian language|Old Nubian]])\n*[[Basque language|Basque]]: {{circa|lk=no}} 1000\n*[[Uralic languages|Uralic]]: 12th century\n**12th century: [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n**{{circa|lk=no}} 1200: [[Finnic languages|Finnic]]\n**14th century: [[Permic languages|Permic]] ([[Komi language|Komi]])\n*[[Mongolic languages|Mongolic]]: 13th century (apparently related [[Khitan language]]: 10th century) \n*[[Kra\u2013Dai]]: 13th century ([[Thai language|Thai]])\n*[[Uto-Aztecan languages|Uto-Aztecan]]: 16th century ([[Classical Nahuatl]])\n*[[Quechuan languages|Quechuan]]: 16th century\n*[[Niger\u2013Congo]] ([[Bantu languages|Bantu]]): 16th century ([[Kongo language|Kikongo]])\n*[[Northwest Caucasian languages|Northwest Caucasian]]: 17th century ([[Abkhaz language|Abkhaz]], [[Adyghe language|Adyghe]], [[Ubykh language|Ubykh]])\n*[[Indigenous Australian languages]]: 18th century\n*[[Iroquoian languages|Iroquoian]]: 19th century ([[Cherokee language|Cherokee]])\n*[[Hmong\u2013Mien languages|Hmong-Mien]]: 20th century\n\n==Constructed languages==\n{{Further|Constructed language}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Language !! Attestation !! Notes\n|-\n| 1879 || [[Volap\u00fck]] || ||   created by [[Johann Martin Schleyer]]\n|-\n| 1887 || [[Esperanto]] || ''[[Unua Libro]]'' ||  created by [[L. L. Zamenhof]]\n|-\n| 1907 || [[Ido language|Ido]] || || based on Esperanto\n|-\n| 1917 || [[Quenya]] || || created by [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]\n|-\n| 1928 || [[Novial]] || ||  created by [[Otto Jespersen]]\n|-\n| 1935 || [[Sona language (artificial)|Sona]] || ''Sona, an auxiliary neutral language'' ||  created by [[Kenneth Searight]]\n|-\n| 1943 || Interglossa|| ''Later became [[Glosa]]'' ||  created by [[Lancelot Hogben]]\n|-\n| 1951 || [[Interlingua]] || [[Interlingua-English Dictionary]] ||   created by the [[International Auxiliary Language Association]]\n|-\n| 1955 || [[Loglan]] || || created by [[James Cooke Brown]]\n|-\n| 1984 || [[Klingon language|Klingon]] || ''[[Star Trek III: The Search for Spock]]'' ||  created by [[Marc Okrand]]\n|-\n| 1987 || [[Lojban]] || || based on [[Loglan]], created by the Logical Language Group\n|-\n| 2001 || [[Atlantean language|Atlantean]] || ''[[Atlantis: The Lost Empire]]'' ||  created by [[Marc Okrand]]\n|-\n| 2005\u20136 || [[Na'vi language|Na'vi]] || ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]] || created by Dr. [[Paul Frommer]] and [[James Cameron]]\n|-\n| 2009 || [[Dothraki language|Dothraki]] || || created by [[George R. R. Martin]] and [[David J. Peterson]] for ''[[Game of Thrones]]''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of writing]]\n*[[List of writing systems]]\n*[[Undeciphered writing systems]]\n*[[Origin of language]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n;Works cited\n*{{citation\n | first = Robert | last = Bagley | authorlink = Robert Bagley\n | chapter = Shang Archaeology | pages = 124\u2013231\n | editor1-first = Michael | editor1-last = Loewe\n | editor2-first = Edward L. | editor2-last = Shaughnessy\n | title = The Cambridge History of Ancient China\n | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge\n | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0-521-47030-8\n | postscript = .\n| title-link = The Cambridge History of Ancient China }}\n*{{citation\n | first = Philip | last = Baldi\n |author-link = Philip Baldi\n | title = The Foundations of Latin\n | publisher = Walter de Gruyter | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-3-11-017208-9\n | postscript = .\n}}\n*{{citation\n | first = David N. | last = Keightley | authorlink = David N. Keightley\n | chapter = The Shang: China's first historical dynasty | pages = 232\u2013291\n | editor1-first = Michael | editor1-last = Loewe\n | editor2-first = Edward L. | editor2-last = Shaughnessy\n | title = The Cambridge History of Ancient China\n | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge\n | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0-521-47030-8\n | postscript = .\n}}\n*{{citation\n | first = Bhadriraju | last = Krishnamurti | authorlink = Bhadriraju Krishnamurti\n | title = The Dravidian Languages\n | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-0-521-77111-5\n | postscript = .\n}}\n*{{citation\n | first = J.-P. | last = Olivier\n | title = Cretan Writing in the Second Millennium B.C\n | journal = World Archaeology  | volume = 17  | issue = 3  | year = 1986\n | pages = 377\u2013389  | doi = 10.1080/00438243.1986.9979977\n | postscript = .\n}}\n*{{citation\n | last = Pollock | first = Sheldon\n | title = The Language of the Gods in the World of Men: Sanskrit, Culture, and Power in Premodern India\n | publisher = University of California Press | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-0-520-24500-6\n | postscript = .\n}}\n*{{citation | first = Roger D. | last = Woodard | chapter = Language in ancient Europe: an introduction | pages = [https://archive.org/details/ancientlanguages00roge/page/1 1\u201313] | title = The Ancient Languages of Europe | editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodard | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68495-8 | postscript = . | url = https://archive.org/details/ancientlanguages00roge/page/1 }}\n*{{citation\n | last = Woods | first = Christopher (ed.)\n | title = Visible Language: Inventions of Writing in the Ancient Middle East and Beyond\n | publisher = The Oriental Institute of the University of Chicago | location = Chicago\n | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-1-885923-76-9\n | url = http://oi.uchicago.edu/pdf/oimp32.pdf\n | postscript = .\n}}\n\n{{Writing systems}}\n{{list of writing systems}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Languages By First Written Accounts}}\n[[Category:Earliest known manuscripts by language| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of languages|First]]\n[[Category:Lists of firsts|Languages]]\n[[Category:Language histories|*]]\n[[Category:Historical linguistics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{sprotected2}}\nThis is a list of [[language]]s arranged by the approximate dates of the oldest existing [[writing|texts]] recording a complete sentence in the language.  It does not include [[undeciphered scripts]], though there are various claims without wide acceptance, which, if substantiated, would push backward the first attestation of certain languages.  It also does not include inscriptions consisting of isolated words or names from a language.\nIn most cases, some form of the language had already been spoken (and even written) considerably earlier than the dates of the earliest extant samples provided here.\n\nA written record may encode a stage of a language corresponding to an earlier time, either as a result of [[oral tradition]], or because the earliest source is a copy of an older manuscript that was lost. An oral tradition of [[epic poetry]] may typically bridge a few centuries, and in rare cases, over a millennium. An extreme case is the [[Vedic Sanskrit]] of the ''[[Rigveda]]'': the earliest parts of this text may date to {{circa|lk=no}} 1500 BC,<ref>{{cite book\n| chapter = Sanskrit | first = Stephanie W. | last = Jamison | pages = 6\u201332\n| title = The Ancient Languages of Asia and the Americas\n| editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodward\n| publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68494-1\n}} pp. 6\u20137.</ref> while the oldest known manuscripts date to {{circa|lk=no}} 1040 AD.<ref>{{cite book\n| chapter = The Development of the Vedic Canon and its Schools : The Social and Political Milieu\n| first = Michael | last = Witzel\n| pages = 257\u2013348\n| chapter-url = http://www.people.fas.harvard.edu/~witzel/canon.pdf\n| title = Inside the Texts, Beyond the Texts\n| editor-first = Michael | editor-last = Witzel\n| publisher = Harvard University Department of Sanskrit and Indian Studies\n| location = Cambridge, MA | year = 1997\n| isbn = 978-1-888789-03-4\n}} p. 259.</ref>\nSimilarly the oldest [[Avestan language|Avestan]] texts, the ''[[Gathas]]'', are believed to have been composed before 1000 BC, but the oldest Avestan manuscripts date from the 13th century AD.<ref>{{cite book\n| chapter = Avestan | first = Mark | last = Hale | pages = 101\u2013122\n| title = The Ancient Languages of Asia and the Americas\n| editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodward\n| publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68494-1\n}}</ref>\n\nFor languages that have developed out of a known predecessor, dates provided here follow conventional terminology. For example, [[Old French]] developed gradually out of [[Vulgar Latin]], and the [[Oaths of Strasbourg]] (842) listed are the earliest text that is classified as \"Old French\".\n\n==Before 1000 BC==\n{{Further|Bronze Age writing}}\nWriting first appeared in the [[Near East]] at the beginning of the 3rd millennium BC.  A very limited number of languages are attested in the area from before the [[Bronze Age collapse]] and the rise of [[alphabetic writing]]:\n* the [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]], [[Hurrian language|Hurrian]], [[Hattic language|Hattic]] and [[Elamite language]] isolates,\n* [[Afro-Asiatic]] in the form of the [[Ancient Egyptian language|Egyptian]] and [[Semitic languages]] and\n* [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] ([[Anatolian languages]] and [[Mycenaean Greek]]).\nIn [[East Asia]] towards the end of the second millennium BC, the [[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]] family was represented by [[Old Chinese]].\n\nThere are also a number of [[undeciphered writing systems|undeciphered]] Bronze Age records:\n* [[Proto-Elamite script]] and [[Linear Elamite]]\n* the [[Indus script]] (claimed to record a \"[[Harappan language]]\")\n* [[Cretan hieroglyphs]] and [[Linear A]] (encoding a possible \"[[Minoan language]]\"){{sfnp|Woodard|2008|p=2}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archaeology.about.com/od/lterms/qt/linear_a.htm |title=Linear A \u2013 Undeciphered Writing System of the Minoans |publisher=Archaeology.about.com |date=2013-07-13 |accessdate=2013-09-17}}</ref>\n* the [[Cypro-Minoan syllabary]]{{sfnp|Woodard|2008|p=3}}\nEarlier symbols, such as the [[Jiahu symbols]], [[Vin\u010da symbols]] and the marks on the [[Dispilio tablet]], are believed to be [[proto-writing]], rather than representations of language.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Language !! Attestation !! Notes\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 2690 BC || [[Egyptian language|Egyptian]] || [[Egyptian hieroglyphs]] in the tomb of [[Seth-Peribsen]] ([[Second Dynasty of Egypt|2nd Dynasty]]), [[Umm el-Qa'ab]]<ref name=\"James Egyptian\">{{cite book |title=The Ancient Egyptian Language |surname=Allen |given=James P. |author-link=James Peter Allen |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2003 |isbn=978-1-107-66467-8 |page=2 }}</ref>\n|\"proto-hieroglyphic\" inscriptions from about 3300 BC ([[Naqada III]]; see [[Abydos, Egypt]], [[Narmer Palette]])\n|-\n| 26th&nbsp;century&nbsp;BC || [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]] || ''[[Instructions of Shuruppak]]'', the [[Kesh temple hymn]] and other [[cuneiform]] texts from [[Shuruppak]] and [[Abu Salabikh]] ([[Fara period]])<ref>{{cite book |last=Hayes |first=John |year=1990 |title=A Manual of Sumerian: Grammar and Texts |publisher=UNDENA |location=Malibu, CA. |isbn=978-0-89003-197-1 |pages=268\u2013269}}</ref>{{sfnp|Woods |2010|p=87}}\n|\"proto-literate\" period from about 3500 BC (see [[Kish tablet]]); administrative records at [[Uruk]] and [[Ur]] from {{circa|lk=no}} 2900 BC.\n|-\n|c. 2400 BC\n|[[Canaanite languages|Canaanite]]\n|Semitic protective spells attested in an Egyptian inscription in the [[pyramid of Unas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2007/01/070129100250.htm|title=Earliest Semitic Text Revealed In Egyptian Pyramid Inscription|website=ScienceDaily|language=en|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hebrew-academy.org.il/2013/05/21/%d7%9c%d7%97%d7%a9%d7%99%d7%9d-%d7%91%d7%a7%d7%93%d7%9d-%d7%9b%d7%a0%d7%a2%d7%a0%d7%99%d7%aa-%d7%91%d7%9b%d7%aa%d7%91%d7%99-%d7%94%d7%a4%d7%99%d7%a8%d7%9e%d7%99%d7%93%d7%95%d7%aa-%d7%a1%d7%a7%d7%99/|title=\u05dc\u05d7\u05e9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d1\u05e7\u05d3\u05dd\u05be\u05db\u05e0\u05e2\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea \u05d1\u05db\u05ea\u05d1\u05d9 \u05d4\u05e4\u05d9\u05e8\u05de\u05d9\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea: \u05e1\u05e7\u05d9\u05e8\u05d4 \u05e8\u05d0\u05e9\u05d5\u05e0\u05d4 \u05e9\u05dc \u05ea\u05d5\u05dc\u05d3\u05d5\u05ea \u05d4\u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05d1\u05d0\u05dc\u05e3 \u05d4\u05e9\u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05d9 \u05dc\u05e4\u05e1\u05d4\"\u05e0 {{!}} \u05d4\u05d0\u05e7\u05d3\u05de\u05d9\u05d4 \u05dc\u05dc\u05e9\u05d5\u05df \u05d4\u05e2\u05d1\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea|website=hebrew-academy.org.il|language=he-IL|access-date=2019-01-06|date=2013-05-21}}</ref>\n|Initial attempts at deciphering the texts failed due to Egyptologists mistaking the Semitic spells for Egyptian, thus rendering them unintelligible.\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 2400 BC || |[[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] || A few dozen pre-Sargonic texts from [[Mari, Syria|Mari]] and other sites in northern Babylonia<ref>{{cite book | title = Sargonic Akkadian: A Historical and Comparative Study of the Syllabic Texts | first = R