ription of [[Tish-atal]] in [[Urkesh]]<ref>{{cite book | editor1-first = Alexander J. | editor1-last = De Voogt | editor2-first = Irving L. | editor2-last = Finkel | title = The Idea of Writing: Play and Complexity | publisher = BRILL | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-90-04-17446-7 | chapter = The adaptation of Cuneiform script to foreign languages | first = Wilfred H. | last = van Soldt | pages = 117\u2013128 }}</ref> || \n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1700 BC || [[Hittite language|Hittite]] || [[Anitta]] text in [[Hittite cuneiform]]<ref name=\"Watkins Hittite\">{{cite book | chapter = Hittite | first = Calvert | last = Watkins | pages = 6\u201330 | title = The Ancient Languages of Asia Minor | editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodard | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68496-5 }}</ref> || Isolated Hittite words and names occur in Assyrian texts found at [[K\u00fcltepe]], from the 19th century BC.<ref name=\"Watkins Hittite\"/>\n|-\n| 16th&nbsp;century&nbsp;BC || [[Palaic language|Palaic]] || [[Hittite texts]] CTH 751\u2013754<ref>{{cite book | chapter = Palaic | first = H. Craig | last = Melchert | pages = 40\u201345 | title = The Ancient Languages of Asia Minor | editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodard | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68496-5 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1450 BC || [[Mycenaean Greek language|Mycenaean Greek]] || [[Linear B]] tablet archive from [[Knossos]]<ref>{{cite web|first=Cynthia|last=Shelmerdine|authorlink=Cynthia W. Shelmerdine|title=Where Do We Go From Here? And How Can the Linear B Tablets Help Us Get There?|url=http://www2.ulg.ac.be/archgrec/IMG/aegeum/aegaeum18(pdf)/34%20Shelmerdine.pdf|accessdate=2008-03-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003195005/http://www2.ulg.ac.be/archgrec/IMG/aegeum/aegaeum18%28pdf%29/34%20Shelmerdine.pdf|archivedate=2011-10-03}}</ref>{{sfnp|Olivier|1986|pp=377f}}<ref>{{cite web | title = Clay tablets inscribed with records in Linear B script | publisher = British Museum | url = https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/gr/c/tablets_with_linear_b_script.aspx | access-date = 7 May 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150504061641/http://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/gr/c/tablets_with_linear_b_script.aspx | archive-date = 2015-05-04 | url-status = dead }}</ref> || These are mostly administrative lists, with some complete sentences.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Aegean scripts |first=Emmett L. |last=Bennett |author-link=Emmett L. Bennett, Jr. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195079937/page/125 125\u2013133] |title=The World's Writing Systems |editor-first1=Peter T. |editor-last1=Daniels |editor-first2=William |editor-last2=Bright |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-19-507993-7 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195079937/page/125 }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1400 BC || [[Luwian language|Luwian]] || [[Hieroglyphic Luwian]] monumental inscriptions, Cuneiform Luwian tablets in the Hattusa archives{{sfnp|Baldi|2002|p=30}} || Isolated hieroglyphs appear on seals from the 18th century BC.{{sfnp|Baldi|2002|p=30}}\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1400 BC || [[Hattic language|Hattic]] || [[Hittite texts]] CTH 725\u2013745 || \n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1300 BC || [[Ugaritic language|Ugaritic]] || Tablets from [[Ugarit]]<ref>{{cite book|first=Dennis|last=Pardee|chapter=Ugaritic|pages=5\u201335|editor-first=Roger D.|editor-last=Woodard|title=The Ancient Languages of Syria-Palestine and Arabia|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-521-68498-9}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1200 BC || [[Old Chinese]] || [[Oracle bone]] and [[Chinese bronze inscriptions|bronze inscriptions]] from the reign of [[Wu Ding]]{{sfnp|Bagley|1999|pp=181\u2013182}}{{sfnp|Keightley|1999|pp=235\u2013237}}<ref>{{cite book|first=John|last=DeFrancis|title=Visible Speech. The Diverse Oneness of Writing Systems|chapter=Chinese|pages=89\u2013121|chapterurl=http://www.pinyin.info/readings/texts/visible/index.html|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|year=1989|isbn=978-0-8248-1207-2}}</ref> || \n|}\n<gallery heights=\"150px\" widths=\"150px\">\nFile:Peribsen2.JPG|Seal impression from the tomb of [[Seth-Peribsen]], containing the oldest known complete sentence in [[Egyptian language|Egyptian]], {{circa|lk=no}} 2690 BC<ref name=\"James Egyptian\"/>\nFile:Letter Luenna Louvre AO4238.jpg|Letter in [[Sumerian cuneiform]] sent by the high-priest Lu'enna, informing the king of [[Lagash]] of his son's death in battle, {{circa|lk=no}} 2400 BC<ref>{{cite web |title=Lettre du grand-pr\u00eatre Lu'enna |publisher=Louvre |url=http://cartelfr.louvre.fr/cartelfr/visite?srv=car_not&idNotice=9732 |access-date=16 September 2018 }}</ref>\nFile:NAMA Linear B tablet of Pylos.jpg|Greek [[Linear B]] tablet from [[Pylos]], recording the distribution of hides, {{circa|lk=no}} 1200 BC\nFile:Shang dynasty inscribed scapula.jpg|Ox scapula inscribed with three records of divinations in the reign of [[Wu Ding]] of the Chinese [[Shang dynasty]], {{circa|lk=no}} 1200 BC\n</gallery>\n\n==First millennium BC==\n\n[[File:Sarcophag of Ahiram inscription.png|thumb|right|upright=2.2|The [[Ahiram]] epitaph is the earliest substantial inscription in [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]].]]\nThe earliest known alphabetic inscriptions, at [[Serabit el-Khadim]] ({{circa|lk=no}} 1500 BC), appear to record a [[Northwest Semitic]] language, though only one or two words have been deciphered.\nIn the [[Early Iron Age]], alphabetic writing spread across the Near East and southern Europe. With the emergence of the [[Brahmic family of scripts]], [[languages of India]] are attested from after about 300 BC.\n\nThere is only fragmentary evidence for languages such as [[Iberian language|Iberian]], [[Tartessian language|Tartessian]], [[Galatian language|Galatian]], [[Thracian language|Thracian]] and [[Messapian language|Messapian]].{{sfnp|Woodard|2008|pp=4, 9, 11}}\nThe [[North Picene language]] of the Novilara Stele from {{circa|lk=no}} 600 BC has not been deciphered.{{sfnp|Woodard|2008|p=4}}\nThe earliest examples of the Central American [[Isthmian script]] date from {{circa|lk=no}} 500 BC, but a proposed decipherment remains controversial.<ref>{{cite book | title = Lost Languages: The Enigma of the World's Undeciphered Scripts | first = Andrew | last = Robinson | publisher = Thames & Hudson | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-500-51453-5 | page = 263}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Language !! Attestation !! Notes\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1000 BC || [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]] || [[Ahiram]] epitaph<ref>{{cite journal | first = Edward M. | last = Cook | title = On the Linguistic Dating of the Phoenician Ahiram Inscription (KAI 1) | journal = Journal of Near Eastern Studies | volume = 53 | issue = 1 | year = 1994 | pages = 33\u201336 | jstor = 545356 | doi=10.1086/373654}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 10th century BC || [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] || royal inscriptions from [[Aramean]] city-states<ref>{{cite book|first=Stuart|last=Creason|chapter=Aramaic|pages=108\u2013144|editor-first=Roger D.|editor-last=Woodard|title=The Ancient Languages of Syria-Palestine and Arabia|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-521-68498-9}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 10th century BC || [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] or [[Phoenician language|Phoenician]] || [[Gezer calendar]]<ref>{{cite journal| title = The Gezer Calendar and Northwest Semitic Linguistics | first = Daniel | last = Silvan | journal = Israel Exploration Journal | volume = 48 | issue = 1/2 | year = 1998 | pages = 101\u2013105 | jstor = 27926502}}</ref> || [[Paleo-Hebrew]] employed a slightly modified Phoenician alphabet, hence the uncertainty between which is attested to here. \n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 850 BC || [[Ammonite language|Ammonite]] || [[Amman Citadel Inscription]]<ref>{{cite journal | title = The Ammn Citadel Inscription: A New Collation | first = William J. | last = Fulco | journal = Bulletin of the American Schools of Oriental Research | volume = 230 | issue = 230 | year = 1978 | pages = 39\u201343 | jstor = 1356612 | doi = 10.2307/1356612 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 840 BC || [[Moabite language|Moabite]] || [[Mesha Stele]] ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 800 BC || [[Phrygian language|Phrygian]] || Paleo-Phrygian inscriptions at [[Gordion]]<ref>{{cite book | first = Claude | last = Brixhe | chapter = Phrygian | pages = 69\u201380 | title = The Ancient Languages of Asia Minor | editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodard | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68496-5 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 8th century BC || [[Sabaean language|Sabaean]] ([[Old South Arabian]]) || mainly [[boustrophedon]] inscriptions from Yemen<ref>{{cite book|first1=Norbert|last1=Nebes|first2=Peter|last2=Stein|chapter=Ancient South Arabian|pages=145\u2013178|editor-first=Roger D.|editor-last=Woodard|title=The Ancient Languages of Syria-Palestine and Arabia|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2008|isbn=978-0-521-68498-9}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 700 BC || [[Etruscan language|Etruscan]] || proto-Corinthian vase found at [[Tarquinia]]<ref>{{cite book | title = Part 2 of The Cambridge Ancient History: The Hellenistic World | editors = F. W. Walbank, A. E. Astin, M. W. Frederiksen | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 1990 | isbn = 978-0-521-23446-7 | page = 12 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 7th century BC || [[Latin]] || ''Vetusia'' Inscription and ''[[Praeneste fibula|Fibula Praenestina]]''<ref>{{cite book|title=A Companion to the Latin Language|first=James|last=Clackson|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|year=2011|isbn=978-1-4443-4336-6|page=13|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HgQjpHUIBWkC&pg=PA13&lpg=PA13}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 600 BC || [[Lydian language|Lydian]] || inscriptions from [[Sardis]]{{sfnp|Baldi|2002|p=30}} ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 600 BC 