[Palani]] have been claimed as [[Tamil-Brahmi]],<ref>{{Cite book\n| chapter=Situating Iron Age moduments in South Asia: a textual and ethnographic approach\n| first=K. |last=Rajan\n| url=https://books.google.com/?id=VAb9CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA311\n| title=A Companion to South Asia in the Past\n| editor1-first=Gwen | editor1-last=Robbins Schug | editor2-first=Subhash R. | editor2-last=Walimbe\n| publisher = Wiley-Blackwell | year=2016| isbn = 978-1-119-05548-8| pages = 310\u2013318\n}} p. 311.</ref><ref>{{Cite book\n| url=http://iks.iitgn.ac.in/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/Iron-Age%E2%80%93Early-Historical-transition-in-South-India-K-Rajan.pdf\n| title=Iron Age \u2013 Early Historic Transition in South India: an appraisal\n| first=K. | last=Rajan | publisher = Institute of Archaeology | year=2014| page = 9\n}}</ref> but this is disputed.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Owner's graffiti on pottery from Tissamaharama |first=Harry| last=Falk| journal=Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Arch\u00e4ologie Au\u00dfereurop\u00e4ischer Kulturen |volume=6 | year=2014| page=46, with footnote 2| url=https://www.academia.edu/11754083}} Falk has criticized the Kodumanal and Porunthal claims as \"particularly ill-informed\"; Falk argues that some of the earliest supposed inscriptions are not Brahmi letters at all, but merely misinterpreted non-linguistic [[Megalithic graffiti symbols]], which were used in South India for several centuries during the pre-literate era.</ref> Pottery fragments dated to the 6th century BC and inscribed with personal names have been found at [[Keeladi]],<ref>{{cite report\n| title=Keeladi: an Urban Settlement of Gangam Age on the Banks of the River Vigai\n| editor1-first=R. | editor1-last=Sivanantham | editor2-first=M. | editor2-last=Seran\n| location=Chennai | publisher=Department of Archaeology, Government of Tamil Nadu | year=2019\n| pages=8\u20139, 14\n}}</ref> but the dating is disputed.<ref>{{cite journal\n| title = Experts Question Dates of Script in Tamil Nadu's Keeladi Excavation Report\n| given = Sukanya | surname = Charuchandra\n| journal = The Wire | date = 17 October 2019\n| url = https://thewire.in/the-sciences/keeladi-settlement-tamil-nadu-department-of-archaeology-tamil-brahmi-script-indus-valley-civilisation\n}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{0|{{circa|lk=no}}}} 146 BC || [[Numidian language|East Numidian]] || [[Punic-Libyan Inscription]] at [[Dougga]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Mausoleum of Ateban |url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?place=33644&plaA=33644-3-1 |publisher=British Museum }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| 2nd century BC || [[Meroitic language|Meroitic]] || graffiti on the temple of [[Amun]] at Dukki Gel, near [[Kerma]]<ref>{{cite book | title=The Meroitic Language and Writing System | first1=Claude | last1=Rilly | first2=Alex | last2=de Voogt | publisher=Cambridge University Press | year=2012 | isbn=978-1-139-56053-5 | page=6 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 100 BC || [[Celtiberian language|Celtiberian]] || [[Botorrita plaques]] ||\n|-\n| 1st century BC || [[Parthian language|Parthian]] || ostraca at [[Nisa, Iran|Nisa]] and [[Qumis, Iran|Qumis]]<ref>{{cite book | title=History of Civilizations of Central Asia, volume 3 | editor-first=B.A | editor-last=Litvinsky | chapter=Sassanian Iran: Intellectual Life, Part One: Written Works | first=A. | last=Tafazzoli | pages=81\u201394 | publisher=UNESCO | year=1996 | isbn=978-92-3-103211-0 | chapter-url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0010/001046/104612e.pdf | postscript=, }} page 94.</ref> ||\n|-\n| 1st century BC || [[Sanskrit]] || [[Ayodhya Inscription of Dhana]], and [[Hathibada Ghosundi Inscriptions]] (both near [[Chittorgarh]])<ref>{{cite book | title = Indian Epigraphy: A Guide to the Study of Inscriptions in Sanskrit, Prakrit, and the other Indo-Aryan Languages | first = Richard | last = Salomon | publisher = Oxford University Press | year = 1998 | isbn = 978-0-19-535666-3 | pages = 86\u201387 }}</ref> || The [[Junagadh rock inscription of Rudradaman]] (shortly after 150 AD) is the oldest long text.<ref>Salomon (1998), p. 89.</ref>\n|}\n\n==First millennium AD==\nFrom [[Late Antiquity]], we have for the first time languages with earliest records in [[manuscript]] tradition (as opposed to [[epigraphy]]). Thus, [[Old Armenian]] is first attested in the [[Armenian Bible translation]].\n\nThe [[Vimose inscriptions]] (2nd and 3rd centuries) in the [[Elder Futhark]] runic alphabet appear to record [[Proto-Norse language|Proto-Norse]] names. Some scholars interpret the [[Negau helmet]] inscription ({{circa|lk=no}} 100 BC) as a Germanic fragment.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Language !! Attestation !! Notes\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 150 || [[Bactrian language|Bactrian]] || [[Rabatak inscription]] ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 200 || [[Proto-Norse language|Proto-Norse]] || inscription ''NITHIJO TAWIDE'' on shield grip from the [[Illerup \u00c5dal]] [[Roman Iron Age weapon deposits|weapon deposit]] || Single Proto-Norse words are found on the [[\u00d8vre Stabu spearhead]] (second half of the 2nd century) and the [[Vimose Comb]] (c. 160).\n|-\n| {{0|{{circa|lk=no}}}} 292 || [[Mayan languages|Mayan]] || Stela 29 from [[Tikal]]<ref>{{cite book\n| chapter = Mayab | first = Victoria R. | last = Bricker | pages = 163\u20131922\n| title = The Ancient Languages of Asia and the Americas\n| editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodward\n| publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68494-1\n}}</ref> || A brief undeciphered inscription at [[San Bartolo (Maya site)|San Bartolo]] is dated to the 3rd century BC.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Early Maya Writing at San Bartolo, Guatemala | first1 = William A. | last1 = Saturno | first2 = David | last2 = Stuart | first3 = Boris | last3 = Beltr\u00e1n | journal = Science | volume = 311 | issue = 5765 | pages = 1281\u20131283 | year = 2006 | url = http://www.sanbartolo.org/science.pdf | doi = 10.1126/science.1121745 | pmid=16400112| bibcode = 2006Sci...311.1281S }}</r