cripts<ref>{{cite book |chapter=A Glimpse into the Tocharian Vinaya Texts |surname=Pan |given=Tao |pages=67\u201392 |chapter-url=https://www.academia.edu/34338196 |title=Rules of Engagement: Medieval Traditions of Buddhist Monastic Regulation |editor1-given=Susan |editor1-surname=Andrews |editor2-given=Jinhua |editor2-surname=Chen |editor3-given=Cuilan |editor3-surname=Liu |publisher=Numata Center for Buddhist Studies |year=2017 |isbn=978-3-89733428-1 }}</ref> || Some Tocharian names and words have been found in Prakrit documents from [[Kror\u00e4n]] dated {{circa|lk=no}} 300.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Bronze Age languages of the Tarim Basin | first=J.P. | last=Mallory | journal=Expedition | volume=52 | issue=3 | pages=44\u201353 | year=2010 | url=http://penn.museum/documents/publications/expedition/PDFs/52-3/mallory.pdf }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 430 || [[Georgian language|Georgian]] || [[Bir el Qutt inscriptions]]<ref>{{cite book | last = Hewitt | first = B.G. | title = Georgian: A Structural Reference Grammar | publisher = John Benjamins | year = 1995 | isbn = 978-90-272-3802-3 | page = 4 }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 450 || [[Kannada]] || [[Halmidi inscription]]{{sfnp|Krishnamurti|2003|p=23}} || ''[[Kavirajamarga]]'' ({{circa|lk=no}} 850) is the oldest literary work.{{sfnp|Krishnamurti|2003|p=23}}\n|-\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 500 || [[Armenian language|Armenian]] || inscription at the [[Tekor Basilica]]<ref>{{cite book | chapter = Classical Armenian | first = James P.T. | last = Clackson | pages = 124\u2013144 | title = The Ancient Languages of Asia Minor | editor-first = Roger D. | editor-last = Woodard | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-521-68496-5 }}</ref> || [[Saint Mesrob Mashtots]] is traditionally held to have translated an [[Armenian Bible]] in 434.\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 510 || [[Old Dutch]] || formula for freeing a serf in the ''Malbergse Glossen'' on the [[Salic law]]<ref name=\"Willemyns\">{{cite book | tit