arz]], culminating in [[Walter Roth]]'s ''The Structure of the Koko Yimidir Language'' in 1901.<ref>{{cite book | first = Walther | last = Roth | title = North Queensland Ethnography, Bulletin 2: The Structure of the Koko Yimidir Language | publisher = Government Printer | location = Brisbane | year = 1910 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first = John B. | last = Haviland | chapter = Guugu Yimidhirr | pages = 26\u2013181 | chapter-url = http://pages.ucsd.edu/~jhaviland/Publications/GYGrammar1.pdf | editor1-first = R. M. W. | editor1-last = Dixon | editor2-first = Barry J. | editor2-last = Blake | title = Handbook of Australian Languages, Volume 1 | publisher = John Benjamins | location = Canberra | year = 1979 | isbn = 978-90-272-7355-0 }} p. 35</ref> || A list of 61 words recorded in 1770 by [[James Cook]] and [[Joseph Banks]] was the first written record of an Australian language.<ref name = \"JH\">{{cite journal | first = John B. | last = Haviland | title = A last look at Cook's Guugu Yimidhirr word list | journal = Oceania | volume = 44 | number = 3 | year = 1974 | pages = 216\u2013232 | jstor = 40329896 | url = http://pages.ucsd.edu/~jhaviland/Publications/HavilandOceania.pdf | doi = 10.1002/j.1834-4461.1974.tb01803.x }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{0|{{circa|lk=no}}}} 1891 || [[Galela language|Galela]] || grammatical sketch by M.J. van Baarda<ref name=\"Voorhoeve\">{{ cite book | chapter = A hundred years of Papuan Linguistic Research: Western New Guinea Area | first = C.L. | last = Voorhoeve | pages = 117\u2013141 | chapter-url = http://papuaweb.org/dlib/bk/pl/C38/02-1-1.pdf | title = New Guinea Area Languages and Language Study, Volume 1: Papuan Languages and the New Guinea Linguistic Scene | editor-first = Stephen A. | editor-last = Wurm | publisher = Australian National University | year = 1975 | url = http://papuaweb.org/dlib/bk/pl/C38/_toc.html }}</ref> ||\n|-\n| {{0|{{circa|lk=no}}}} 1893 || [[Oromo language|Oromo]] || translation of the [[New Testament]] by [[Onesimos Nesib]], assisted by [[Aster Ganno]] ||\n|-\n| {{0|{{circa|lk=no}}}} 1903 || [[Lingala language|Lingala]] || grammar by Egide de Boeck ||\n|-\n| {{0|{{circa|lk=no}}}} 1905 || [[Istro-Romanian language|Istro-Romanian]] || ''Calindaru lu rumeri din Istrie'' by [[Andrei Glavina]] and [[Constantin Diculescu]]<ref name=\"glavina\">{{cite web|url=http://istro-romanian.com/history/1992_curtis-lingua-storia.htm|title=La lingua, la storia, la tradizione degli istroromeni|first=Ervino|last=Curtis|publisher=Associazione di Amicizia Italo-Romena Decebal|year=1992|location=Trieste|pp=6\u201313|language=it}}</ref> || Compilation of Istro-Romanian popular words, proverbs and stories.<ref name=\"glavina\" /> ||\n|-\n| {{circa|lk=no}} 1940 || [[Kamoro language|Kamoro]] || materials by [[Peter Drabbe]]<ref name=\"Voorhoeve\"/> || A Kamoro wordlist recorded in 1828 by Modera and M\u00fcller, passengers on a Dutch ship, is the oldest record of any of the [[Papuan languages]].<ref name=\"Voorhoeve\"/><ref>{{cite book | title = The Papuan Languages of New Guinea | first = William A. | last = Foley | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 1986 | isbn = 978-0-521-28621-3 | page = 13 }}</ref>\n|-\n| {{0|{{circa|lk=no}}}} 1968 || [[Southern Ndebele language|Southern Ndebele]] || small booklet published with praises of their kings and a little history || A translation of the [[New Testament]] of the [[Bible]] was completed in 1986; translation of the [[Old Testament]] is ongoing.\n|-\n| {{0|{{circa|lk=no}}}} 1982 || [[Gooniyandi language|Gooniyandi]] || survey by William McGregor<ref>{{cite book | title = A Functional Grammar of Gooniyandi | first = William | last = McGregor | publisher = John Benjamins | year = 1990 | isbn = 978-90-272-3025-6 | page = 26 }}</ref> ||\n|}\n\n==By family==\nAttestation by major [[language family]]:\n*[[Afro-Asiatic]]: since about the 27th century BC\n**27th century BC: [[Egyptian language|Egyptian]]\n**24th century BC: [[Semitic languages|Semitic]] ([[Eblaite language|Eblaite]], [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]])\n**7th century AD: [[Cushitic languages|Cushitic]] ([[Beja language|Beja]])\n*[[Hurro-Urartian languages|Hurro-Urartian]]: {{circa|lk=no}} 21st century BC\n*[[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]]: since about the 17th century BC\n**17th century BC: [[Anatolian languages|Anatolian]] ([[Hittite language|Hittite]])\n**15th century BC: [[Greek language|Greek]]\n**7th century BC: [[Italic languages|Italic]] ([[Latin language|Latin]])\n**6th century BC: [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] ([[Lepontic language|Lepontic]])\n**{{circa|lk=no}} 500 BC: [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] ([[Old Persian]])\n**4th century AD: [[Germanic languages|Germanic]] ([[Gothic language|Gothic]])\n**9th century AD: [[Balto-Slavic languages|Balto-Slavic]] ([[Old Church Slavonic]])\n*[[Sino-Tibetan languages|Sino-Tibetan]]: {{circa|lk=no}} 1200 BC\n**{{circa|lk=no}} 1200 BC: [[Old Chinese]]\n**8th century AD: [[Tibeto-Burman]] ([[Tibetic languages|Tibetan]])\n*[[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]]: {{circa|lk=no}} 200 BC ([[Tamil language|Tamil]])\n*[[Mayan languages|Mayan]]: 3rd century AD\n*[[Austronesian languages|Austronesian]]: 4th century AD ([[Cham language|Cham]])\n*[[South Caucasian languages|South Caucasian]]: 5th century ([[Georgian language|Georgian]])\n*[[Northeast Caucasian languages|Northeast Caucasian]]: 7th century ([[Udi language|Udi]])\n*[[Austroasiatic]]: 7th century ([[Khmer language|Khmer]])\n*[[Turkic languages|Turkic]]: 8th century ([[Old Turkic]])\n*[[Japonic]]: 8th century\n*[[Nilo-Saharan]]: 8th century ([[Old Nubian language|Old Nubian]])\n*[[Basque language|Basque]]: {{circa|lk=no}} 1000\n*[[Uralic languages|Uralic]]: 12th century\n**12th century: [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n**{{circa|lk=no}} 1200: [[Finnic languages|Finnic]]\n**14th century: [[Permic languages|Permic]] ([[Komi language|Komi]])\n*[[Mongolic languages|Mongolic]]: 13th century (apparently related [[Khitan language]]: 10th century) \n*[[Kra\u2013Dai]]: 13th century ([[Thai language|Thai]])\n*[[Uto-Aztecan languages|Uto-Aztecan]]: 16th century ([[Classical Nahuatl]])\n*[[Quechuan languages|Quechuan]]: 16th century\n*[[Niger\u2013Congo]] ([[Bantu languages|Bantu]]): 16th century ([[Kongo language|Kikongo]])\n*[[Northwest Caucasian languages|Northwest Caucasian]]: 17th century ([[Abkhaz language|Abkhaz]], [[Adyghe language|Adyghe]], [[Ubykh language|Ubykh]])\n*[[Indigenous Australian languages]]: 18th century\n*[[Iroquoian languages|Iroquoian]]: 19th century ([[Cherokee language|Cherokee]])\n*[[Hmong\u2013Mien languages|Hmong-Mien]]: 20th century\n\n==Constructed languages==\n{{Further|Constructed language}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date !! Language !! Attestation !! Notes\n|-\n| 1879 || [[Volap\u00fck]] || ||   created by [[Johann Martin Schleyer]]\n|-\n| 1887 || [[Esperanto]] || ''[[Unua Libro]]'' ||  created by [[L. L. Zamenhof]]\n|-\n| 1907 || [[Ido language|Ido]] || || based on Esperanto\n|-\n| 1917 || [[Quenya]] || || created by [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]\n|-\n| 1928 || [[Novial]] || ||  created by [[Otto Jespersen]]\n|-\n| 1935 || [[Sona language (artificial)|Sona]] || ''Sona, an auxiliary neutral language'' ||  created by [[Kenneth Searight]]\n|-\n| 1943 || Interglossa|| ''Later became [[Glosa]]'' ||  created by [[Lancelot Hogben]]\n|-\n| 1951 || [[Interlingua]] || [[Interlingua-English Dictionary]] ||   created by the [[International Auxiliary Language Association]]\n|-\n| 1955 || [[Loglan]] || || created by [[James Cooke Brown]]\n|-\n| 1984 || [[Klingon language|Klingon]] || ''[[Star Trek III: The Search for Spock]]'' ||  created by [[Marc Okrand]]\n|-\n| 1987 || [[Lojban]] || || based on [[Loglan]], created by the Logical Language Group\n|-\n| 2001 || [[Atlantean language|Atlantean]] || ''[[Atlantis: The Lost Empire]]'' ||  created by [[Marc Okrand]]\n|-\n| 2005\u20136 || [[Na'vi language|Na'vi]] || ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]] || created by Dr. [[Paul Frommer]] and [[James Cameron]]\n|-\n| 2009 || [[Dothraki language|Dothraki]] || || created by [[George R. R. Martin]] and [[David J. Peterson]] for ''[[Game of Thrones]]''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of writing]]\n*[[List of writing systems]]\n*[[Undeciphered writing systems]]\n*[[Origin of language]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n;Works cited\n*{{citation\n | first = Robert | last = Bagley | authorlink = Robert Bagley\n | chapter = Shang Archaeology | pages = 124\u2013231\n | editor1-first = Michael | editor1-last = Loewe\n | editor2-first = Edward L. | editor2-last = Shaughnessy\n | title = The Cambridge History of Ancient China\n | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge\n | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0-521-47030-8\n | postscript = .\n| title-link = The Cambridge History of Ancient China }}\n*{{citation\n | first = Philip | last = Baldi\n |author-link = Philip Baldi\n | title = The Foundations of Latin\n | publisher = Walter de Gruyter | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-3-11-017208-9\n | postscript = .\n}}\n*{{citation\n | first = David N. | last = Keightley | authorlink = David N. Keightley\n | chapter = The Shang: China's first historical dynasty | pages = 232\u2013291\n | editor1-first = Michael | editor1-last = Loewe\n | editor2-first = Edward L. | editor2-last = Shaughnessy\n | title = The Cambridge History of Ancient China\n | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge\n | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0-521-47030-8\n | postscript = .\n}}\n*{{citation\n | first = Bhadriraju | last = Krishnamurti | authorlink = Bhadriraju Krishnamurti\n | title = The Dravidian Languages\n | publisher = Cambridge University Press | year = 2003 | isbn = 978-0-521-77111-5\n | postscript = .\n}}\n*{{citation\n | first = J.-P. | last = Olivier\n | title = Cretan Writing in the Second Millennium B.C\n | journal = World Archaeology  | volume = 17  | issue = 3  | year = 1986\n | pages = 377\u2013389  | doi = 10.1080/00438243.1986.9979977\n | postscript = .\n}}\n*{{citation\n