nal links==\n{{wikisource|Select Historical Documents of the Middle Ages/Book II/The Salic Law|The Salic Law}}\n* [http://www.leges.uni-koeln.de/en/lex/lex-salica/ Information on the ''Salic law'' and its manuscript tradition on the ''{{lang|la|Bibliotheca legum regni Francorum manuscripta}}'' website], A database on Carolingian secular law texts (Karl Ubl, Cologne University, Germany).\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Latin prose texts]]\n[[Category:French law]]\n[[Category:Old Dutch]]\n[[Category:Earliest known manuscripts by language]]\n[[Category:6th-century Latin books]]\n[[Category:6th century in Francia]]\n[[Category:6th century in law]]\n[[Category:6th-century Frankish writers]]\n[[Category:6th-century jurists]]\n[[Category:Succession acts]]\n", "name_user": "Srnec", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salic_law"}
{"title_page": "Vectorman", "text_new": "{{short description|Multilevel platform video game series for Sega}}'''''Vectorman''''' is a series of [[Shoot 'em up#Run and gun|run and gun]] [[platform game|platform]] [[video game|video games]] [[video game developer|developed]] by [[BlueSky Software]] and [[video game publisher|published]] by [[Sega]] for the [[Sega Genesis|Sega Mega Drive/Genesis]]. \n\nThe [[Vectorman#Vectorman|first game (of the same name)]] in the series was released in October 1995.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120219134336/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1995_Oct_23/ai_17424312/ Sega begins 24-hour countdown to \"Vectormania\"]</ref> The games have since appeared on several game compilations, including the ''[[Sega Genesis Collection]]'' for the [[PlayStation 2]] and [[PlayStation Portable]], the ''[[Sonic Gems Collection]]'' for the [[GameCube|Nintendo GameCube]], and ''[[Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection]]'' for [[Xbox 360]] and [[PlayStation 3]]. ''Vectorman'' was added to the [[Wii]] [[Virtual Console]] in 2007,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/e0y50PCLy6ekTyFfdiSDBE6EUXRehFaO|title=Two WiiWare Games and Two Virtual Console Games Added to Wii Shop Channel|date=2008-09-22|work=[[Nintendo]]|accessdate=2008-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622220348/https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/e0y50PCLy6ekTyFfdiSDBE6EUXRehFaO|archive-date=June 22, 2018|url-status=dead|publisher=Nintendo of America}}</ref> on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] as part of the ''Sega Genesis Classics Pack'', and as part of the [[Sega Forever]] service in 2018. In 2019, the game was included on the [[Sega Genesis Mini|Sega Genesis/Mega Drive Mini]] console.\n\nIn 1996, a sequel, titled ''[[Vectorman 2]]'', was released.\n\n==Games==\n\n===''Vectorman''===\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Vectorman\n| image = Vectorman cover.jpg\n| caption = North American cover art\n| developer = [[BlueSky Software]]\n| publisher = [[Sega]]\n| producer = Jerry Markota <br> Jenny Cleary\n| designer = Rich Karpp <br> [[Mark Lorenzen]]\n| composer = Jon Holland\n| released = {{vgrelease|NA|October 24, 1995|EU|November 30, 1995}}\n| genre = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n| platforms = [[Sega Genesis|Sega Genesis/Mega Drive]]\n}}\n\n==== Story ====\nIn 2049, the human population of [[Earth]] embarks on a migratory voyage to try to colonize other planets. They leave mechanical \"orbots\" to clean up the mess they made on Earth through [[litter]]ing and [[pollution]]. Raster, a high-level orbot who watches Earth through a planetwide computer network, is accidentally attached to a working [[nuclear weapon|nuclear missile]] by a lesser orbot and goes insane, becoming an evil dictator named Warhead. He declares himself ruler of Earth, and begins preparing to execute any humans who dare return to their planet.\n\nEnter Vectorman, a humble orbot in charge of cleaning up toxic sludge by simply discharging it into the sun. As he lands on Earth after his last trip, he finds chaos and confusion. Because all the other Orbots are controlled by Warhead (Vectorman having not been affected because he was away), Vectorman takes it upon himself to destroy the errant orbot and restore peace to Earth.\n\n==== Graphics and gameplay ====\n''Vectorman'' uses [[Pre-rendering|pre-rendered]] [[3D computer graphics|3D models]] in its level and character designs. This gives the game a smooth, computer-generated feel. The original name of the villain, Warhead, was Raster (as in [[raster graphics]], the opposite of [[vector graphics]]). Vectorman was considered the answer to Nintendo's [[Donkey Kong Country]] at the time, as they both used graphical tricks to show graphics beyond what the console was thought capable of.\n\nThe game itself is a straightforward [[2D computer graphics|2D]] [[Action game|action]] platformer. Vectorman is an \"orbot\" (a robot whose body is composed almost entirely of [[Sphere|orbs]]) powered with a ball gun in his hand; power-ups include a [[machine gun]], \"bolo\" gun, and triple-fire guns.\n\nVectorman possesses the ability to transform, through the use of power-ups, into several different forms: including a drill, to cut through floors; a bomb, to destroy all surrounding enemies or breakable walls; and an aquatic form, useful for swimming underwater. In addition to power-up transformations, three levels host unique morphed forms with which to combat bosses in. Overall, the game consists of 16 levels.\n\n==== Development ====\n''Vectorman'' introduced the then-new Genesis programming technique referred to by Sega as Vector Piece Animation.<ref name=\"GPro882\">{{cite magazine|author=The Whizz|date=January 1996|title=Sega Vectors in on Better Genesis Programming|magazine=[[GamePro]]|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|issue=88|page=28}}</ref> The player character's body actually consists of 23 individual sprites programmed to move in unison.<ref name=\"GPro882\" />\n\n==== Reception ====\nThe four reviewers of ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' gave the first ''Vectorman'' a score of 8.25 out of 10, unanimously praising the advanced graphics and animation, large levels with numerous hidden areas, strong audio, and ability to change into different forms.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=November 1995|title=Review Crew: Vectorman|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|publisher=Sendai Publishing|issue=76|page=42}}</ref> ''[[GamePro]]''{{'}}s Scary Larry gave it a rave review, stating that \"your jaw will hang open in amazement at what Vectorman does with the 16-bit Genesis engine. This platform game comes on with great guns, a morphing hero, and diverse, well-detailed levels.\" He also praised the simple controls, advanced graphics, and sound effects, and scored it a 5/5 in graphics, control, and FunFactor and a 4.5/5 in sound.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=November 1995|title=ProReview: Vectorman|magazine=[[GamePro]]|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|issue=86|pages=70\u201371}}</ref> Both ''Electronic Gaming Monthly'' and ''GamePro'' awarded it Best Genesis Game of 1995.<ref>{{cite journal|year=1996|title=Electronic Gaming Monthly's Buyer's Guide|url=|journal=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|volume=|issue=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=February 1996|title=Editor's Choice Awards 1995|magazine=[[GamePro]]|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|issue=89|page=26}}</ref>\n\n===''Vectorman 2''===\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Vectorman 2\n|image = Vectorman2.jpg\n|caption = Box art\n|developer = [[BlueSky Software]]\n|publisher = [[Sega]]\n|producer = Jerry Markota <br> Jerry Huber\n|designer = John Abad <br> Marty Davis <br> Keith R. Freiheit <br> Jerry Huber <br> Rick Randolph <br> Rick Schmitz <br> Ron Thompson <br> [[Thi Truong]] <br> Jason Weesner <br> Dok Whitson\n|engine =\n|released = {{vgrelease|NA|November 15, 1996}}\n|genre = [[Action game|Action]]/[[platform game]]\n|modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n|platforms = [[Sega Genesis|Sega Genesis/Mega Drive]]\n}}\n\n==== Story ====\nAfter saving Earth from Warhead in the previous game, Vectorman's sludge barge is targeted and destroyed by a missile. Vectorman escapes, parachuting down to the planet to battle with the Earth's multitudinous enemy; [[Mutant (fictional)|mutant]] [[Insect|insects]]. Now it is up to Vectorman to fight through the mutant bugs and find the most fearsome source infestation; the evil [[Latrodectus|Black Widow]] [[Gyne|Queen]].\n\n====Graphics and gameplay====\nThe gameplay is similar to the previous game.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Vectorman 2: So Much Trash, So Little Time |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=88 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=November 1996 |pages=256\u20137}}</ref> Vectorman has a different set of weapons, including a pulse beam, energy shot, and super shot guns. Vectorman can also now transform into animal forms such as a fire ant, a rhino, and a \"shield bug\" that repels attacks. Unlike the original ''Vectorman'', the full-level transformations featured in this game are not used to combat bosses as that is left to the human-form Vectorman. There are 22 levels divided into seven parts in all.\n\nBefore ''Vectorman 2'' was released, [[Sega Channel]] held a contest that allowed artists to draw a morph of Vectorman. Judges then chose the best one to be transformed in Genesis art, as well as being put on the Sega Channel. Ten runner-up submitters won a copy of ''Vectorman 2''.<ref>{{Cite web | title=Sega Channel Memories pt2|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3bvC6RwA88Y|date=2007-06-10|accessdate=2010-02-17}}</ref>\n\n====Reception====\n''Electronic Gaming Monthly'' gave ''Vectorman 2'' a 7.25 out of 10. Shawn Smith, Dan Hsu, and Crispin Boyer applauded its traditional side-scrolling gameplay, huge levels, graphics, and animation, especially on the bosses. Sushi-X, in contrast, said that the levels are surprisingly small, making it a disappointment compared to the first game.<ref>{{cite magazine|last= |first= |title=Review Crew: Vectorman 2|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=88 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=November 1996 |page=90}}</ref> Scary Larry gave it a 4.5/5 in graphics and a 5/5 in every other category. He said that compared to the first game, it \"has cleaner graphics, more sound and voice effects, and faster, smoother gameplay. Add to this spectacular and complex levels, and you have the makings of a Sega classic.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|date=December 1996|title=ProReview: Vectorman 2|url=https://archive.org/details/GamePro_Issue_099_Volume_09_Number_12_1996-12_IDG_Publishing_US/page/n157|magazine=[[GamePro]]|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|issue=99|page=154|pages=|doi=|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> ''Electronic Gaming Monthly'' awarded it Genesis Game of the Year.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Best of '96|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=92 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=March 1997|page=86}}</ref>\n\n==Other Vectorman projects==\nA design document was completed for a third Vectorman title in the series which would have appeared on the [[Sega Saturn]], but BlueSky Software's relationship with Sega ended before the proposal could be reviewed or green-lit. In 2000, six former BlueSky employees formed a new company called VBlank Software<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hxhmDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT168&lpg=PT168&dq=vectorman+vblank&source=bl&ots=MX2MojkNTL&sig=1leQkf9QToDpuwsbOG_tl4tQ2kQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj__em-hLLdAhWG0J8KHVb9DVEQ6AEwB3oECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=vectorman%20vblank&f=false|title=Playing at the Next Level: A History of American Sega Games|last=Horowitz|first=Ken|date=2016-10-21|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9780786499946|language=en}}</ref> to create original titles for the PlayStation 2. One of the projects they created was a demo for a new 3D Vectorman game which would have featured the character on an alien planet with new transformations. However, Sega had already established a relationship with Canadian developer [[Pseudo Interactive]] to create a Vectorman title that was based around a more traditional combat model and had a more serious tone.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/technology/pseudo-interactive-bounces-back-with-physics-engine/article1136767/|title=Pseudo Interactive bounces back with physics engine|last=|first=|date=May 10, 2004|work=The Globe and mail|access-date=2018-09-11}}</ref> VBlank Software never got to present its demo and Sega canceled Pseudo Interactive's Vectorman title after it was briefly shown at the 2003 [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|E3]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1995 video games]]\n[[Category:1996 video games]]\n[[Category:BlueSky Software games]]\n[[Category:Cancelled PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 2043]]\n[[Category:Fictional robots]]\n[[Category:Fictional shapeshifters]]\n[[Category:Mobile games]]\n[[Category:Video games about robots]]\n[[Category:Run and gun games]]\n[[Category:Science fiction video games]]\n[[Category:Sega Games franchises]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis games]]\n[[Category:Sega video games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 1995]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games with 2.5D graphics]]\n[[Category:Video games with pre-rendered 3D graphics]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Multilevel platform video game series for Sega}}'''''Vectorman''''' is a series of [[Shoot 'em up#Run and gun|run and gun]] [[platform game|platform]] [[video game|games]] [[video game developer|developed]] by [[BlueSky Software]] and [[video game publisher|published]] by [[Sega]] for the [[Sega Genesis|Sega Mega Drive/Genesis]]. \n\nThe [[Vectorman#Vectorman|first game (of the same name)]] in the series was released in October 1995.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120219134336/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_1995_Oct_23/ai_17424312/ Sega begins 24-hour countdown to \"Vectormania\"]</ref> The games have since appeared on several game compilations, including the ''[[Sega Genesis Collection]]'' for the [[PlayStation 2]] and [[PlayStation Portable]], the ''[[Sonic Gems Collection]]'' for the [[GameCube|Nintendo GameCube]], and ''[[Sonic's Ultimate Genesis Collection]]'' for [[Xbox 360]] and [[PlayStation 3]]. ''Vectorman'' was added to the [[Wii]] [[Virtual Console]] in 2007,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/e0y50PCLy6ekTyFfdiSDBE6EUXRehFaO|title=Two WiiWare Games and Two Virtual Console Games Added to Wii Shop Channel|date=2008-09-22|work=[[Nintendo]]|accessdate=2008-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622220348/https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/e0y50PCLy6ekTyFfdiSDBE6EUXRehFaO|archive-date=June 22, 2018|url-status=dead|publisher=Nintendo of America}}</ref> on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] as part of the ''Sega Genesis Classics Pack'', and as part of the [[Sega Forever]] service in 2018. In 2019, the game was included on the [[Sega Genesis Mini|Sega Genesis/Mega Drive Mini]] console.\n\nIn 1996, a sequel, titled ''[[Vectorman 2]]'', was released.\n\n==Games==\n\n===''Vectorman''===\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Vectorman\n| image = Vectorman cover.jpg\n| caption = North American cover art\n| developer = [[BlueSky Software]]\n| publisher = [[Sega]]\n| producer = Jerry Markota <br> Jenny Cleary\n| designer = Rich Karpp <br> [[Mark Lorenzen]]\n| composer = Jon Holland\n| released = {{vgrelease|NA|October 24, 1995|EU|November 30, 1995}}\n| genre = [[Platform game|Platform]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n| platforms = [[Sega Genesis|Sega Genesis/Mega Drive]]\n}}\n\n==== Story ====\nIn 2049, the human population of [[Earth]] embarks on a migratory voyage to try to colonize other planets. They leave mechanical \"orbots\" to clean up the mess they made on Earth through [[litter]]ing and [[pollution]]. Raster, a high-level orbot who watches Earth through a planetwide computer network, is accidentally attached to a working [[nuclear weapon|nuclear missile]] by a lesser orbot and goes insane, becoming an evil dictator named Warhead. He declares himself ruler of Earth, and begins preparing to execute any humans who dare return to their planet.\n\nEnter Vectorman, a humble orbot in charge of cleaning up toxic sludge by simply discharging it into the sun. As he lands on Earth after his last trip, he finds chaos and confusion. Because all the other Orbots are controlled by Warhead (Vectorman having not been affected because he was away), Vectorman takes it upon himself to destroy the errant orbot and restore peace to Earth.\n\n==== Graphics and gameplay ====\n''Vectorman'' uses [[Pre-rendering|pre-rendered]] [[3D computer graphics|3D models]] i