{"title_page": "Boys Don't Cry (The Cure album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Boys Don't Cry\n| type       = compilation\n| artist     = [[The Cure]]\n| cover      = Boys_Don't_Cry.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 5 February 1980\n| recorded   = 1978\u20131979\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Post-punk]]\n| length     = 34:09 (CD version)\n| label      = [[Fiction Records|Fiction]] (UK)<br>[[Passport_Records|PVC]] (original US LP)<br>[[Elektra_Records|Elektra]] (later US CD issues)\n| producer   = Chris Parry\n| prev_title = [[Three Imaginary Boys]]\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Seventeen Seconds]]\n| next_year  = 1980\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Boys Don't Cry\n | type        = Compilation\n | single1     = [[Killing an Arab]]\n | single1date = December 1978\n | single2     = [[Boys Don't Cry (The Cure song)|Boys Don't Cry]]\n | single2date = June 1979\n | single3     = [[Jumping Someone Else's Train]]\n | single3date = November 1979\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Boys Don't Cry''''' is [[the Cure]]'s first compilation album.<ref>https://www.post-punk.com/the-cure-boys-dont-cry/</ref> Released in February 1980, this album is composed of several tracks from the band's May 1979 debut album ''[[Three Imaginary Boys]]'' (which had yet to see a U.S. release) with material from the band's 1978-1979 era. \n\n== Release ==\n''Boys Don't Cry'' was released on 5 February 1980 by record label [[Fiction Records|Fiction]]. According to [[AllMusic]], the album \"[falls] somewhere between [an] official release and [[compilation album|compilation]]\", and was released \"in hopes of increasing the band's exposure outside of the U.K.\"<ref name=\"True\"/>\n\nA new version of the title track was released in April 1986.<ref>https://www.discogs.com/The-Cure-Boys-Dont-Cry-New-Voice-Club-Mix/release/5066369</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"True\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/boys-dont-cry-mw0000651837 |title=''Boys Don't Cry'' \u2013 The Cure |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=25 October 2012 |last=True |first=Chris}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Back Catalogue |journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=227 |date=June 2005 |last=Mulholland |first=Garry |page=124}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite book |chapter=The Cure |last=Sheffield |first=Rob |authorlink=Rob Sheffield |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |edition=4th |year=2004 |editor1-last=Brackett |editor1-first=Nathan |editor2-last=Hoard |editor2-first=Christian |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/205 205\u201306] }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev4score = B+<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv4-80.php |title=Christgau's Consumer Guide |newspaper=[[The Village Voice]] |date=28 April 1980 |accessdate=25 October 2012 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Boys Don't Cry'' has been generally well received by critics. Debra Rae Cohen of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote that the album \"proves they can transcend their Comp. Lit. 201 (Elementary Angst) scenarios\".<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/boys-dont-cry-19800821 |title=''Boys Don't Cry'' |journal=[[Rolling Stone]]  |last=Cohen |first=Debra Rae |date=21 August 1980 |accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' called the band's sound \"dry post-punk, never pretty but treated with a properly mnemonic pop overlay\" and was more reserved in his praise, adding, \"I can look over the titles and recall a phrase from all but a few of these 13 songs. Intelligent phrases they are, too, yet somehow I find it hard to get really excited about them\".<ref name=\"Christgau\"/>\n\nIn 2000 it was voted number 775 in [[Colin Larkin]]'s ''[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]''.<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]|author=[[Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=3rd|isbn=0-7535-0493-6|page=244}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the album was ranked at No. 442 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|list of the 500 best albums ever]]. In the 2012 update of the same list, it moved up the list to No. 438.<ref name=\"500-greatest\">{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/the-cure-boys-dont-cry-35195/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time Rolling Stone\u2019s definitive list of the 500 greatest albums of all time| publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate= September 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n\n{{track listing\n| all_writing = The Cure ([[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]], [[Michael Dempsey]] and [[Lol Tolhurst]])\n| headline = Side A\n| title1 = [[Boys Don't Cry (The Cure song)|Boys Don't Cry]]\n| length1 = 2:37\n| title2 = Plastic Passion\n| length2 = 2:15\n| title3 = [[10:15 Saturday Night]]\n| length3 = 3:40\n| title4 = Accuracy\n| length4 = 2:16\n| title5 = Object\n| length5 = 3:03\n| title6 = [[Jumping Someone Else's Train]]\n| length6 = 2:58\n| title7 = Subway Song\n| length7 = 1:54\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title1 = [[Killing an Arab]]\n| length1 = 2:22\n| title2 = Fire in Cairo\n| length2 = 3:21\n| title3 = Another Day\n| length3 = 3:43\n| title4 = Grinding Halt\n| length4 = 2:49\n| title5 = World War\n| length5 = 2:36\n| title6 = Three Imaginary Boys\n| length6 = 3:14\n}}\n\n: <small>On most CD versions of the album, \"Object\" was replaced by \"So What\", the scream at the end of \"Subway Song\" was shortened and \"World War\" was removed.</small>\n\n== Personnel ==\n'''The Cure'''\n\n* [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]] \u2013 guitar, vocals, harmonica\n* [[Michael Dempsey]] \u2013 bass guitar, vocals\n* [[Lol Tolhurst]] \u2013 drums\n\n'''Technical'''\n\n*[[Chris Parry (producer)|Chris Parry]] \u2013 [[record producer|production]]\n\n==Certifications and sales==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|title=Boys Don't cry|type=album|artist=The Cure|relyear=1983|certyear=1986|region=France|award=Gold|certref=<ref>{{cite web|title=Les Certifications depuis 1973: Albums|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Album_Certifications.php|publisher=Infodisc.fr|accessdate=1 June 2019}} (select \"The Cure\" from drop-down list)</ref>}}\n{{certification Table Entry|title=Boys don't cry|type=album|artist=The Cure|region=United Kingdom|award=Gold|certyear=1991|relyear=1983}}\n{{certification Table Bottom}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Discogs master|20161|Boys Don't Cry}}\n\n{{The Cure}}\n\n[[Category:The Cure albums]]\n[[Category:1980 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Fiction Records compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Elektra Records compilation albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Boys Don't Cry\n| type       = compilation\n| artist     = [[The Cure]]\n| cover      = Boys_Don't_Cry.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 5 February 1980\n| recorded   = 1978\u20131979\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Post-punk]]\n| length     = 34:09 (CD version)\n| label      = [[Fiction Records|Fiction]] (UK)<br>[[Passport_Records|PVC]] (original US LP)<br>[[Elektra_Records|Elektra]] (later US CD issues)\n| producer   = Chris Parry\n| prev_title = [[Three Imaginary Boys]]\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Seventeen Seconds]]\n| next_year  = 1980\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Boys Don't Cry\n | type        = Compilation\n | single1     = [[Killing an Arab]]\n | single1date = December 1978\n | single2     = [[Boys Don't Cry (The Cure song)|Boys Don't Cry]]\n | single2date = June 1979\n | single3     = [[Jumping Someone Else's Train]]\n | single3date = November 1979\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Boys Don't Cry''''' is [[the Cure]]'s first compilation album.<ref>https://www.post-punk.com/the-cure-boys-dont-cry/</ref> Released in February 1980, this album is composed of several tracks from the band's May 1979 debut album ''[[Three Imaginary Boys]]'' (which had yet to see a U.S. release) with material from the band's 1978-1979 era. \n\n== Release ==\n''Boys Don't Cry'' was released on 5 February 1980 by record label [[Fiction Records|Fiction]]. According to [[AllMusic]], the album \"[falls] somewhere between [an] official release and [[compilation album|compilation]]\", and was released \"in hopes of increasing the band's exposure outside of the U.K.\"<ref name=\"True\"/>\n\nA new version of the title track was released in April 1986.<ref>https://www.discogs.com/The-Cure-Boys-Dont-Cry-New-Voice-Club-Mix/release/5066369</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"True\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/boys-dont-cry-mw0000651837 |title=''Boys Don't Cry'' \u2013 The Cure |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=25 October 2012 |last=True |first=Chris}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Back Catalogue |journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=227 |date=June 2005 |last=Mulholland |first=Garry |page=124}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev3score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite book |chapter=The Cure |last=Sheffield |first=Rob |authorlink=Rob Sheffield |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |edition=4th |year=2004 |editor1-last=Brackett |editor1-first=Nathan |editor2-last=Hoard |editor2-first=Christian |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/205 205\u201306] }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev4score = B+<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news |url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv4-80.php |title=Christgau's Consumer Guide |newspaper=[[The Village Voice]] |date=28 April 1980 |accessdate=25 October 2012 |last=Christgau |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Christgau}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Boys Don't Cry'' has been generally well received by critics. Debra Rae Cohen of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote that the album \"proves they can transcend their Comp. Lit. 201 (Elementary Angst) scenarios\".<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/boys-dont-cry-19800821 |title=''Boys Don't Cry'' |journal=[[Rolling Stone]]  |last=Cohen |first=Debra Rae |date=21 August 1980 |accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref> [[Robert Christgau]] of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' called the band's sound \"dry post-punk, never pretty but treated with a properly mnemonic pop overlay\" and was more reserved in his praise, adding, \"I can look over the titles and recall a phrase from all but a few of these 13 songs. Intelligent phrases they are, too, yet somehow I find it hard to get really excited about them\".<ref name=\"Christgau\"/>\n\nIn 2000 it was voted number 775 in [[Colin Larkin]]'s ''[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]''.<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[All Time Top 1000 Albums]]|author=[[Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=2000|edition=3rd|isbn=0-7535-0493-6|page=244}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the album was ranked at No. 442 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|list of the 500 best albums ever]]. In the 2012 update of the same list, it moved up the list to No. 438.<ref name=\"500-greatest\">{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/the-cure-boys-dont-cry-35195/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time Rolling Stone\u2019s definitive list of the 500 greatest albums of all time| publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate= September 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\n\n{{track listing\n| all_writing = The Cure ([[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]], [[Michael Dempsey]] and [[Lol Tolhurst]])\n| headline = Side A\n| title1 = [[Boys Don't Cry (The Cure song)|Boys Don't Cry]]\n| length1 = 2:37\n| title2 = Plastic Passion\n| length2 = 2:15\n| title3 = [[10:15 Saturday Night]]\n| length3 = 3:40\n| title4 = Accuracy\n| length4 = 2:16\n| title5 = Object\n| length5 = 3:03\n| title6 = [[Jumping Someone Else's Train]]\n| length6 = 2:58\n| title7 = Subway Song\n| length7 = 1:54\n}}\n{{track listing\n| headline = Side B\n| title1 = [[Killing an Arab]]\n| length1 = 2:22\n| title2 = Fire in Cairo\n| length2 = 3:21\n| title3 = Another Day\n| length3 = 3:43\n| title4 = Grinding Halt\n| length4 = 2:49\n| title5 = World War\n| length5 = 2:36\n| title6 = Three Imaginary Boys\n| length6 = 3:14\n}}\n\n: <small>On most CD versions of the album, \"Object\" was replaced by \"So What\", the scream at the end of \"Subway Song\" was shortened and \"World War\" was removed.</small>\n\n== Personnel ==\n'''The Cure'''\n\n* [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]] \u2013 guitar, vocals, harmonica\n* [[Michael Dempsey]] \u2013 bass guitar, vocals\n* [[Lol Tolhurst]] \u2013 drums\n\n'''Technical'''\n\n* Chris Parry \u2013 [[record producer|production]]\n\n==Certifications and sales==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|title=Boys Don't cry|type=album|artist=The Cure|relyear=1983|certyear=1986|region=France|award=Gold|certref=<ref>{{cite web|title=Les Certifications depuis 1973: Albums|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Album_Certifications.php|publisher=Infodisc.fr|accessdate=1 June 2019}} (select \"The Cure\" from drop-down list)</ref>}}\n{{certification Table Entry|title=Boys don't cry|type=album|artist=The Cure|region=United Kingdom|award=Gold|certyear=1991|relyear=1983}}\n{{certification Table Bottom}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Discogs master|20161|Boys Don't Cry}}\n\n{{The Cure}}\n\n[[Category:The Cure albums]]\n[[Category:1980 compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Fiction Records compilation albums]]\n[[Category:Elektra Records compilation albums]]\n", "name_user": "DPUH", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boys_Don%27t_Cry_(The_Cure_album)"}
{"title_page": "Somalia national football team", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{About|the men's team|the women's team|Somalia women's national football team}}\n{{Infobox national football team\n| Name               = Somalia \n| Nickname           = Ocean Stars\n| Badge              = Somali FF (logo).png\n| Badge_size         = \n| FIFA Trigramme     = SOM\n| Association        = [[Somali Football Federation]]\n| Sub-confederation  = [[Council for East and Central Africa Football Associations|CECAFA]] <br> (Central & East Africa)\n| Confederation      = [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] (Africa)\n| Coach              = [[Abdihamid Moalin]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brightwebtv.com/sports/bashiru-hayford-appointed-as-national-head-coach-of-somalia/|title=Bashiru Hayford appointed as National Head Coach of Somalia|last=admin|date=13 March 2019|website=The Spot Of Latest Trending News And Leaks|language=en|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47695877|title=Ghana's Bashir Hayford confirmed as Somalia coach|date=25 March 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n| Asst Manager       = \n| Captain            = [[Ahmed Said Ahmed]] \n| Most caps          = [[Ciise Aden Abshir]] (34)\n| Top scorer         = [[Ciise Aden Abshir]] (22)\n| Home Stadium       = [[Mogadishu Stadium]]\n| FIFA Rank          = {{FIFA World Rankings|SOM}}\n| FIFA max           = 158\n| FIFA max date      = April\u2013June 1995\n| FIFA min           = 207\n| FIFA min date      = April\u2013May 2018\n| Elo Rank           = {{World Football Elo Ratings|Somalia}}\n| Elo max = 126\n| Elo max date = 1973\n| Elo min = 207\n| Elo min date = 2015\n| pattern_la1        = _Somalia16h\n| pattern_b1         = _Somalia16h\n| pattern_ra1        = _Somalia16h\n| pattern_sh1        = _Somalia16h\n| pattern_so1        = _band_blue\n| leftarm1           = 99D9EA\n| body1              = 99D9EA\n| rightarm1          = 99D9EA\n| shorts1            = 99D9EA\n| socks1             = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la2        = _adidas_stripes\n| pattern_b2         = _chelsea1617h1\n| pattern_ra2        = _adidas_stripes\n| pattern_sh2        = _white stripes\n| pattern_so2        = _band_blue\n| leftarm2           = 0000FF\n| body2              = 0000FF\n| rightarm2          = 0000FF\n| shorts2            = 0000FF\n| socks2             = 0000FF\n| First game         = {{fb|Kenya|colonial}} 5\u20130 {{fb-rt|SOM}} <br> ([[Mombasa]], [[Kenya]]; 1958)<ref name=\"Mshassan\">{{cite book|last1=Hassan|first1=Mohammed Sheik|title=History of Somali football (1938\u20132007)|date=2008|publisher=Scansom|page=20|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=m5MaAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref>\n| Largest win        = {{fb|SOM}} 5\u20132 {{fb-rt|MTN|1959}} <br> ([[Casablanca]], [[Morocco]]; 7 August 1985)<br>{{fb|DJI}} 1\u20134 {{fb-rt|SOM}}<br>([[Djibouti]]; January 6, 2019)\n| Largest loss       = {{fb|PRK|1948}} 14\u20130 {{fb-rt|SOM}} <br> ([[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]]; 12 November 1963)\n}}\nThe '''Somalia national footballers team''' ({{lang-so|Xeegada Qaranka Soomaaliya}}), nicknamed the ''Ocean Stars'', represents [[Somalia]] in international [[association football|football]] and is controlled by the [[Somali Football Federation]] (SFF), a member of the [[Confederation of African Football]] (CAF).\n\n==History==\nThe first Somali football teams were established in the 1940s. The competitions were basic in structure, and were associated with the anti-colonial movement. The [[Somali Youth League]] (SYL), the nation's first political party, had put together a team of local youth to play against the Italian expatriate teams. The soccer team the FYL had assembled, which would later change its name to Bondhere, won the first several competitions. In 1951, the [[Somali Football Federation]] (SFF) was founded. The first Somali commissioner for sport was later established in 1958.\n\nAlthough the Somali national football team took part in preliminary matches, it has never qualified for the final stages of a [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]]. For many years after the outbreak of the [[Somali Civil War|civil war]] in the early 1990s, FIFA-sanctioned games could not be played within the country. Qualifying matches for the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] and the World Cup were instead contested away from home. However, following the pacification of the capital [[Mogadishu]] in 2011, the SFF began preparations for the first major sporting event to be held in years at the [[Mogadishu Stadium]], in December 2012.\n\nPrior to 2019, the Somali FA decided they would admit to all their young and upcoming youth talents and put out local trials to fortify both Olympic and national football teams.\n\nIn addition, many from the Somali diaspora in the past have produced quality football players such as Islam Feiruz and Mukhtar Ali.\n\nOn 5 September 2019, Somalia won their first qualifying match since 1984 (against [[Kenya national football team|Kenya]] - AFCON Qualifying) and their first ever FIFA World Cup qualifying match, beating [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]] by 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49621822|title=World Cup qualifying: Somalia national team's history-making driving instructor|website=BBC News|date=8 September 2019}}</ref> They nearly advanced to the second round but lost 3\u20131 in Zimbabwe after two late goals for the warriors, consigning the Ocean Stars to an early exit.\n\n==Coaches==\n[[File:Somalia national team talks with coach Livingstone Mbabazi.jpg|thumbnail|Head coach Charles Livingstone Mbabazi, having talks with the players during a training session.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Name\n!Nat\n!Period\n!Matches\n!Wins\n!Draws\n!Losses\n!Efficiency %\n|-\n|align=\"left\" |[[Qi Wusheng]]\n|{{flagicon|CHN}}\n|1978\u20131979\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Anas Shido\n| {{flagicon|SOM}}\n| 1984-1987\n| 28\n| 19\n| 7\n| 2\n