htwebtv.com/sports/bashiru-hayford-appointed-as-national-head-coach-of-somalia/|title=Bashiru Hayford appointed as National Head Coach of Somalia|last=admin|date=13 March 2019|website=The Spot Of Latest Trending News And Leaks|language=en|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47695877|title=Ghana's Bashir Hayford confirmed as Somalia coach|date=25 March 2019|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n| Asst Manager       = \n| Captain            = [[Ahmed Said Ahmed]] \n| Most caps          = [[Ciise Aden Abshir]] (34)\n| Top scorer         = [[Ciise Aden Abshir]] (22)\n| Home Stadium       = [[Mogadishu Stadium]]\n| FIFA Rank          = {{FIFA World Rankings|SOM}}\n| FIFA max           = 158\n| FIFA max date      = April\u2013June 1995\n| FIFA min           = 207\n| FIFA min date      = April\u2013May 2018\n| Elo Rank           = {{World Football Elo Ratings|Somalia}}\n| Elo max = 126\n| Elo max date = 1973\n| Elo min = 207\n| Elo min date = 2015\n| pattern_la1        = _Somalia16h\n| pattern_b1         = _Somalia16h\n| pattern_ra1        = _Somalia16h\n| pattern_sh1        = _Somalia16h\n| pattern_so1        = _band_blue\n| leftarm1           = 99D9EA\n| body1              = 99D9EA\n| rightarm1          = 99D9EA\n| shorts1            = 99D9EA\n| socks1             = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la2        = _adidas_stripes\n| pattern_b2         = _chelsea1617h1\n| pattern_ra2        = _adidas_stripes\n| pattern_sh2        = _white stripes\n| pattern_so2        = _band_blue\n| leftarm2           = 0000FF\n| body2              = 0000FF\n| rightarm2          = 0000FF\n| shorts2            = 0000FF\n| socks2             = 0000FF\n| First game         = {{fb|Kenya|colonial}} 5\u20130 {{fb-rt|SOM}} <br> ([[Mombasa]], [[Kenya]]; 1958)<ref name=\"Mshassan\">{{cite book|last1=Hassan|first1=Mohammed Sheik|title=History of Somali football (1938\u20132007)|date=2008|publisher=Scansom|page=20|url=https://www.google.com/books?id=m5MaAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref>\n| Largest win        = {{fb|SOM}} 5\u20132 {{fb-rt|MTN|1959}} <br> ([[Casablanca]], [[Morocco]]; 7 August 1985)<br>{{fb|DJI}} 1\u20134 {{fb-rt|SOM}}<br>([[Djibouti]]; January 6, 2019)\n| Largest loss       = {{fb|PRK|1948}} 14\u20130 {{fb-rt|SOM}} <br> ([[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]]; 12 November 1963)\n}}\nThe '''Somalia national footballers team''' ({{lang-so|Xeegada Qaranka Soomaaliya}}), nicknamed the ''Ocean Stars'', represents [[Somalia]] in international [[association football|football]] and is controlled by the [[Somali Football Federation]] (SFF), a member of the [[Confederation of African Football]] (CAF).\n\n==History==\nThe first Somali football teams were established in the 1940s. The competitions were basic in structure, and were associated with the anti-colonial movement. The [[Somali Youth League]] (SYL), the nation's first political party, had put together a team of local youth to play against the Italian expatriate teams. The soccer team the FYL had assembled, which would later change its name to Bondhere, won the first several competitions. In 1951, the [[Somali Football Federation]] (SFF) was founded. The first Somali commissioner for sport was later established in 1958.\n\nAlthough the Somali national football team took part in preliminary matches, it has never qualified for the final stages of a [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]]. For many years after the outbreak of the [[Somali Civil War|civil war]] in the early 1990s, FIFA-sanctioned games could not be played within the country. Qualifying matches for the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] and the World Cup were instead contested away from home. However, following the pacification of the capital [[Mogadishu]] in 2011, the SFF began preparations for the first major sporting event to be held in years at the [[Mogadishu Stadium]], in December 2012.\n\nPrior to 2019, the Somali FA decided they would admit to all their young and upcoming youth talents and put out local trials to fortify both Olympic and national football teams.\n\nIn addition, many from the Somali diaspora in the past have produced quality football players such as Islam Feiruz and Mukhtar Ali.\n\nOn 5 September 2019, Somalia won their first qualifying match since 1984 (against [[Kenya national football team|Kenya]] - AFCON Qualifying) and their first ever FIFA World Cup qualifying match, beating [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]] by 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49621822|title=World Cup qualifying: Somalia national team's history-making driving instructor|website=BBC News|date=8 September 2019}}</ref> They nearly advanced to the second round but lost 3\u20131 in Zimbabwe after two late goals for the warriors, consigning the Ocean Stars to an early exit.\n\n==Coaches==\n[[File:Somalia national team talks with coach Livingstone Mbabazi.jpg|thumbnail|Head coach Charles Livingstone Mbabazi, having talks with the players during a training session.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Name\n!Nat\n!Periodhjjh\n!Matches\n!Wins\n!Draws\n!Losses\n!Efficiency %\n|-\n|align=\"left\" |[[Qi Wusheng]]\n|{{flagicon|CHN}}\n|1978\u20131979\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Anas Shido\n| {{flagicon|SOM}}\n| 1984-1987\n| 28\n| 19\n| 7\n| 2\n| 59%\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Hussein Ali Abdulle]]\n| {{flagicon|SOM}}\n| May 1999 \u2013 Dec 2000\n| 8\n| 0\n| 1\n| 7\n| 6.3%\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | Awil Ismail Mohamed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://somchess.net/xskcagta-oo-sheegay-in-helitaanka-garoon-heer-caalami-ah-ay-is-badal-ku-yeelan-doonto-tayada-ciyaartoyda-sawirro/somali-fa-technical-director-awil-ismail-mohamed/|title=Somali-FA-technical-director-Awil-Ismail-Mohamed - Somchess.net|website=somchess.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200211140004.html|title=Kenya/Somalia: Don't Write Off Somalia, Says Coach|date=14 November 2002|publisher=|via=AllAfrica}}</ref>\n| {{flagicon|SOM}}\n| 2004\u20132005\n| 5\n| 0\n| 1\n| 4