\"#fff3f3\"|'''51.53%''' ''3,070''\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|48.47% ''2,888''\n|align=\"center\" |0.00% ''0''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#fff3f3\"|[[Missouri gubernatorial election, 1980|1980]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#fff3f3\"|40.19% ''2,490''\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|'''59.60%''' ''3,692''\n|align=\"center\" |0.21% ''13''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|[[Missouri gubernatorial election, 1976|1976]]\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#fff3f3\"|42.21% ''2,260''\n|align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0ff\"|'''57.70%''' ''3,089''\n|align=\"center\" |0.09% ''5''\n|}\n\n===State===\nSte. Genevieve County is divided into two legislative districts in the [[Missouri House of Representatives]].\n\n* District 115 is currently represented by [http://house.mo.gov/member.aspx?year=2017&district=115 Elaine Gannon] (R-[[De Soto, Missouri|De Soto]]). Consists of the extreme northern part of the county along the Jefferson County line.\n{{Election box begin|title=Missouri House of Representatives \u2014 District 115 \u2014 Ste. Genevieve County (2016)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = '''Elaine Gannon'''\n  |votes      = '''656'''\n  |percentage = '''62.71%'''\n  |change     = '''+2.54'''\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Barbara Stocker\n  |votes      = 333\n  |percentage = 31.84%\n  |change     = -2.70\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Libertarian Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Charles Bigelow\n  |votes      = 57\n  |percentage = 5.45%\n  |change     = +5.45\n  }}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=Missouri House of Representatives \u2014 District 115 \u2014 Ste. Genevieve County (2014)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = '''Elaine Gannon'''\n  |votes      = '''284'''\n  |percentage = '''60.17%'''\n  |change     = '''+14.02'''\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Dan Darian\n  |votes      = 163\n  |percentage = 34.54%\n  |change     = -19.31\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Constitution Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Jerry Dollar Jr.\n  |votes      = 25\n  |percentage = 5.30%\n  |change     = +5.30\n  }}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=Missouri House of Representatives \u2014 District 115 \u2014 Ste. Genevieve County (2012)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = '''Elaine Gannon'''\n  |votes      = '''474'''\n  |percentage = '''46.15%'''\n  |change     =\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Rich McCane\n  |votes      = 553\n  |percentage = 53.85%\n  |change     =\n  }}\n{{Election box end}}\n* District 116 is currently represented by [http://house.mo.gov/member.aspx?year=2017&district=116 Kevin Engler] (R-[[Farmington, Missouri|Farmington]]). Consists of most of the entire county. In the general elections of 2012, 2014, and 2016 Engler has not an opponent.\n\nAll of Ste. Genevieve County is a part of Missouri's 3rd District in the [[Missouri Senate]] and is currently represented by [http://www.senate.mo.gov/mem03/ Gary Romine] (R-[[Farmington, Missouri|Farmington]]). The 3rd Senatorial District consists of [[Iron County, Missouri|Iron]], [[Reynolds County, Missouri|Reynolds]],  [[St. Francois County, Missouri|St. Francois]], Ste. Genevieve and [[Washington County, Missouri|Washington]] counties and part of [[Jefferson County, Missouri|Jefferson County]]. In 2012, Romine defeated Democrat Joseph Fallert Jr., a state representative with four terms, by winning the entire 3rd District, although Fallert won Ste. Genevieve County.\n{{Election box begin|title=Missouri Senate \u2014 District 3 \u2014 Ste. Genevieve County (2016)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = '''Gary Romine'''\n  |votes      = '''6,328'''\n  |percentage = '''83.25%'''\n  |change     = '''+44.82'''\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Green Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Edward R. Weissler\n  |votes      = 1,273\n  |percentage = 16.75%\n  |change     = +16.75\n  }}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=Missouri Senate \u2014 District 3 \u2014 Ste. Genevieve County (2012)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = '''Gary Romine'''\n  |votes      = '''3,061'''\n  |percentage = '''38.43%'''\n  |change     =\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Joseph Fallert Jr.\n  |votes      = 4,905\n  |percentage = 61.57%\n  |change     =\n  }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Federal===\n{{Election box begin|title=U.S. Senate \u2014 Missouri \u2014 Ste. Genevieve County (2016)}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party       = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate   = '''Roy Blunt'''\n  |votes       = '''4,096'''\n  |percentage  = '''48.83%'''\n  |change      = '''+14.45'''\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party       = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate   = Jason Kander\n  |votes       = 3,929\n  |percentage  = 46.83%\n  |change      = -12.97\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party       = Libertarian Party (United States)\n  |candidate   = Jonathan Dine\n  |votes       = 203\n  |percentage  = 2.42%\n  |change      = -3.40\n  }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party       = Green Party (United States)\n  |candidate   = Johnathan McFarland\n  |votes       = 99\n  |percentage  = 1.18%\n  |change     