 shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1916 United States presidential election|1916]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|47.9% ''1,137''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''51.4%''' ''1,218''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.7% ''17''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1912 United States presidential election|1912]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|47.6% ''1,100''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''49.2%''' ''1,138''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|3.2% ''74''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1908 United States presidential election|1908]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|48.8% ''1,064''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''50.8%''' ''1,108''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.4% ''9''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Missouri, 1904|1904]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|45.5% ''986''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''53.7%''' ''1,163''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.8% ''18''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Missouri, 1900|1900]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|41.6% ''935''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''57.7%''' ''1,296''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.7% ''15''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1896 United States presidential election|1896]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|41.9% ''903''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''57.8%''' ''1,245''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.2% ''5''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1892 United States presidential election|1892]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|36.0% ''683''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''60.9%''' ''1,155''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|3.1% ''59''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1888 United States presidential election|1888]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|38.9% ''776''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''58.5%''' ''1,167''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.6% ''52''\n|}{{hidden end}}\n\nUnlike many other rural counties throughout Missouri, Ste. Genevieve used to be one of the most reliably Democratic strongholds in presidential elections. [[George W. Bush]] lost Ste. Genevieve County both times in [[2000 United States presidential election|2000]] and [[2004 United States presidential election|2004]]; in 2004, it was one of only four counties (the [[Independent city (United States)|independent city]] of [[St. Louis]], [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]] and [[Jackson County, Missouri|Jackson County]]) that voted for [[John Kerry]]. Unlike other rural counties throughout Missouri, Ste. Genevieve County was one of only nine counties in Missouri that favored [[Barack Obama]] over [[John McCain]] in [[2008 United States presidential election|2008]]. The Democratic dominant streak in Ste. Genevieve County, however, was broken in [[2012 United States presidential election|2012]] when [[Mitt Romney]] carried it by three points over [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]]. This was the first time that a Republican presidential nominee had won Ste. Genevieve County since [[Ronald Reagan]] carried the county in his landslide reelection bid in [[1984 United States presidential election|1984]]. In [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]], Republican [[Donald Trump]], who received much more working class support than a typical Republican which could be seen across many working class and [[Rural America|rural]] counties all across the country just like Ste. Genevieve county received 64% in the county, the most of any Presidential candidate since [[Lyndon Johnson]] in [[1964 United States presidential election|1964]] and the most of any Republican candidate ever.\n\nLike most rural counties throughout Missouri, voters in Ste. Genevieve County generally adhere to socially and culturally [[Conservatism|conservative]] principles but are more moderate or [[Populism|populist]] on economic issues, typical of the [[Dixiecrat]] philosophy. In 2004, Missourians voted on [[Missouri Constitutional Amendment 2 (2004)|a constitutional amendment to define marriage as the union between a man and a woman]]\u2014it overwhelmingly passed Ste. Genevieve County with 75.25 percent of the vote. The initiative passed the state with 71 percent of support from voters as Missouri became the first state to ban [[same-sex marriage]]. In 2006, Missourians voted on [[Missouri Constitutional Amendment 2 (2006)|a constitutional amendment to fund and legalize embryonic stem cell research in the state]]\u2014it failed in Ste. Genevieve County with 56.22 percent voting against the measure. The initiative narrowly passed the state with 51 percent of support from voters as Missouri became one of the first states in the nation to approve [[Embryonic stem cell|embryonic stem cell research]]. Despite Ste. Genevieve County\u2019s longstanding tradition of supporting socially conservative platforms, voters in the county have a penchant for advancing [[Populism|populist]] causes like increasing the [[minimum wage]]. In 2006, Missourians voted on a proposition (Proposition B) to increase the minimum wage in the state to $6.50 an hour\u2014it passed Ste. Genevieve County with 79.26 percent of the vote. The proposition strongly passed every single county in Missouri with 78.99 percent voting in favor as the minimum wage was increased to $6.50 an hour in the state. During the same election, voters in five other states also strongly approved increases in the minimum wage.\n\n===Missouri presidential preference primary (2008)===\n{{Missouri Republican primary, 2008\n| name            =Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri\n| huckabee        =''419'' (32.97%)\n| mccain          ='''''518'' (40.76%)'''\n| romney          =''270'' (21.24%)\n| paul            =''47'' (3.70%)\n}}\n{{Missouri Democratic primary, 2008\n| name            =Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri\n| clinton         ='''''1,922'' (62.36%)'''\n| obama           =''1,050'' (34.07%)\n| edwards         =''85'' (2.76%)\n| uncommitted     =\n}}\nThen [[U.S. Senator]] [[Hillary Clinton]] (D-[[New York (state)|New York]]) received more votes, a total of 1,922, than any candidate from either party in Ste. Genevieve County during the 2008 presidential primary. She also received more votes than the total number of votes cast in the entire Republican Primary in Ste. Genevieve County.\n\n==Communities==\n\n===Cities===\n*[[Bloomsdale, Missouri|Bloomsdale]]\n*[[St. Mary, Missouri|St. Mary]]\n*[[Ste. Genevieve, Missouri|Ste. Genevieve]] (county seat)\n\n===Census-designated places===\n*[[Grayhawk, Missouri|Grayhawk]]\n*[[Ozora, Missouri|Ozora]]\n*[[Weingarten, Missouri|Weingarten]]\n\n===Unincorporated communities===\n{{div col|colwidth=13em}}\n*[[Avon, Missouri|Avon]]\n*[[Brickey's, Missouri|Brickeys]]\n*[[Chestnut Ridge, Missouri|Chestnut Ridge]]\n*[[Clearwater, Missouri|Clearwater]]\n*[[Clement, Missouri|Clement]]\n*[[Coffman, Missouri|Coffman]]\n*[[Copper Mine, Missouri|Copper Mine]]\n*[[Kinsey, Missouri|Kinsey]]\n*[[Lake Forest, Missouri|Lake Forest]]\n*[[Lawrenceton, Missouri|Lawrenceton]]\n*[[Marlo, Missouri|Marlo]]\n*[[Mill, Missouri|Mill]]\n*[[Millers, Missouri|Millers]]\n*[[Minnith, Missouri|Minnith]]\n*[[Mosher, Missouri|Mosher]]\n*[[Needmore, Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri|Needmore]]\n*[[New Offenburg, Missouri|New Offenburg]]\n*[[Pickel, Missouri|Pickel]]\n*[[Quarry Town, Missouri|Quarry Town]] \n*[[River aux Vases, Missouri|River aux Vases]]\n*[[Rocky Ridge, Missouri|Rocky Ridge]]\n*[[Sprott, Missouri|Sprott]]\n*[[Thomure, Missouri|Thomure]]\n*[[Valley View, Sainte Genevieve County, Missouri|Valley View]]\n*[[Womack, Missouri|Womack]]\n*[[Zell, Missouri|Zell]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Ghost towns===\n*[[La Saline, Missouri|La Saline]]\n*[[New Bourbon, Missouri|New Bourbon]]\n\n===Townships===\n* [[Beauvais Township, Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri|Beauvais]]\n* [[Jackson Township, Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri|Jackson]]\n* [[Ste. Genevieve Township, Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri|Ste. Genevieve]]\n* [[Saline Township, Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri|Saline]]\n* [[Union Township, Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri|Union]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Al Agnew]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mulibraries.missouri.edu/specialcollections/platbooks.htm Digitized 1930 Plat Book of Ste. Genevieve County] from [[University of Missouri]] Division of Special Collections, Archives, and Rare Books\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri\n|North = [[Monroe County, Illinois]]\n|Northeast = [[Randolph County, Illinois]]\n|East = \n|Southeast = [[Perry County, Missouri|Perry County]]\n|South = [[St. Francois County, Missouri|St. Francois County]]\n|Southwest = \n|West = [[St. Francois County, Missouri|St. Francois County]]\n|Northwest = [[Jefferson County, Missouri|Jefferson County]]\n}}\n\n{{Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri}}\n{{Geographical features of Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri}}\n{{Missouri}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ste. Genevieve County, Missouri| ]]\n[[Category:Missouri counties on the Mississippi River]]\n[[Category:1812 establishments in Missouri Territory]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1812]]\n", "name_user": "Premeditated Chaos", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eValleys:I know, I know.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ste._Genevieve_County,_Missouri"}
